# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nonverbal-communication
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Kendon was born on 4 April 1934 in London, son of the writer Frank Kendon and Elizabeth Cecilia Phyllis Horne, a school teacher.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] At the University of Cambridge, he read Botany, Zoology and Human Physiology, as well as Experimental Psychology for the Natural Sciences.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] At the University of Oxford, he studied Experimental Psychology, focusing on the temporal organization of utterances in conversation, using Eliot Chapple's chronography.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Then he moved to Cornell University to study directly with Chapple on research leading to his D.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] His thesis topic—communication conduct in face-to-face interaction—spelled out the interests he would pursue in subsequent decades.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] He is noted for his study of gesture and sign languages and how these relate to spoken language.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Phil., he accepted a position in the Institute of Experimental Psychology at Oxford, where he worked in a research group with Michael Argyle and E.R.W.F.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] He initially focused on sign systems in Papua New Guinea and Australian Aboriginal sign languages, before developing a general framework for understanding gestures with the same kind of rigorous semiotic analysis as has been previously applied to spoken language.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Important influences on his theoretical understandings included: Erving Goffman, Albert Scheflen, Ray Birdwhistell, and Gregory Bateson.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Becoming aware of Scheflen's work in 1965, while still at Oxford, he managed to meet him in Philadelphia, where he shared his earliest work; as a result, he was first invited to join William S.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Condon's research team at the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic in 1966-67, and then to join Scheflen's research team at Bronx State Hospital in 1967.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] He never actually worked with Birdwhistell directly, but they were in contact, and he did work with films made available to him by Birdwhistell.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] In 1976 he took up an appointment in Canberra, Australia at the Department of Anthropology in the Research School of Pacific Studies, Australian National University.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] He undertook filming everyday interaction in Papua New Guinea but also was able to record a sign language in use in the valley where he worked where there was a considerable number of deaf persons.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] His publication of this work, in three articles in 1980, proved to be a pioneering study; no other accounts on sign language from this part of the world were to appear until the beginning of the twenty-first century.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] This work was republished as a monograph together with a new essay written by colleagues bringing the original work up to date.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] After this he undertook a major investigation of the sign languages in use among indigenous Australians - these are sign languages used for ritual reasons or for practical reasons in situations where speech might is impractical or inappropriate.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] These are known as alternate sign languages, distinguishing them from primary sign languages developed among deaf people.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Extensive documentation of his research in Australia is available at the library of the Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] In 1988, he returned to Philadelphia, teaching for two years at the Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Kendon then moved to Naples, Italy and undertook fieldwork on the use of gesture in everyday interaction among Neapolitans and also published a translation of a 19th Century book about Neapolitan gesture (by Andrea de Jorio), comparing it to gesturing among the Greeks and Romans.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] In 2004 he published an important general book on the phenomena of gesture which drew extensively on his work in Naples as well as his work in New Guinea and Australia, the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Since then he has published various articles on gesture and related topics, including discussions of the place of gesture in theories about language origins.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] In 2012, he returned to Cambridge, where he spent the rest of his life, associated with the Division of Biological Anthropology at Cambridge, and an Honorary Professor in Psychology and Language Sciences at University College London.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Kendon received research grants from the National Science Foundation, the Wenner-Gren Foundation for Anthropological Research, the American Council of Learned Societies, as well as a Guggenheim Fellowship.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] In addition to teaching at Oxford and Penn, he held positions at Cornell University and Connecticut College in the US, as well as the Università degli Studi di Napoli "L'Orientale", the University of Salerno and the University of Calabria in Italy.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Kendon was a founding editor of the journal *GESTURE* (published by John Benjamins of Amsterdam), along with Cornelia Müller, in 2000.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] He was the sole editor from 2010 to April 2017, when he was replaced by Sotaro Kita.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] In his role as editor of *GESTURE* he was an Ex Officio member of the board of the International Society for Gesture Studies, of which he was elected Honorary President in 2006.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] He edited the book series *Gesture Studies* for John Benjamins, with 9 volumes published between 2007 and 2022.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Colleagues prepared a festschrift in 2014, honoring his contribution to the study of gestures and interaction.
[src:nonverbal-communication/adam-kendon] Kendon married Margaret Rhoads in 1961; they had three children, Gudrun, Benjamin and Angus.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Ayer conducts custom research in an attempt to win the advertising business of Nichols-Shepard Co., a manufacturer of agricultural machinery.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 1895 – Harlow Gale of the University of Minnesota mails questionnaires to gather opinions about advertising from the public.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Waldron conducts qualitative research for Mahin’s Advertising Agency.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 1910s – 1911 can be considered the year marketing research becomes an industry.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] George Frederick leaves his position as editor of *Printers' Ink* to begin his research company, the Business Bourse with clients such as General Electric and the Texas Co.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Eastman creates the Association of National Advertisers which is now known as the Association of National Advertising Managers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] The group’s first project is a postcard questionnaire to determine magazine readership.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] The results introduce the concept of duplication of circulation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Eastman starts his own company, the Eastman Research Bureau which boasts clients such as *Cosmopolitan, Christian Herald*, and General Electric.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Daniel Starch tests reader recognition levels of magazine and newspaper advertisements and editorial content.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] George Gallup begins measuring advertising readership.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] George Gallup validates his survey methodology by using the same tools polling voters during public elections.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] This allows him to successfully compare and validate his study's results against the election’s results.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 1940s – Post World War II, the U.S. sees a large increase in the number of market research companies.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 1950s – Market researchers focus on improving methods and measures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] In their search for a single-number statistic to capture the overall performance of the advertising creative, Day-After-Recall (DAR) is created.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 1960s – Qualitative focus groups gain in popularity.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] In addition, some advertisers call for more rigorous measurement of the in-market effectiveness of advertising in order to provide better accountability for the large amounts being spent on advertising.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] In response, Seymour Smith and Associates, using Advertising Research Foundation data as a jumping-off point, develops the Communicus System, a comprehensive approach to isolating the in-market impact of advertising across media.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 1970s – Computers emerge as business tools, allowing researchers to conduct large-scale data manipulations.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 175) Multiple studies prove DAR (Recall) scores do not predict sales.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] The measure, persuasion, also known as motivation, is validated as a predictor of sales.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] The measure known as “breakthrough” is re-examined by researchers who make a distinction between the attention-getting power of the creative execution (attention) and how well “branded” the ad is (brand linkage).
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Herbert Krugman seeks to measure non-verbal measures biologically by tracking brain wave activities as respondents watch commercials.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] (Krugman) Others experiment with galvanic skin response, voice pitch analysis, and eye-tracking.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 1980s – Researchers begin to view commercials as a “structured flow of experience” rather than a single unit to be rated on the whole, creating moment-by-moment systems such as the dial-a-meter.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 1990s – Ameritest Research creates Picture Sorts to provide accurate non-verbal measurements in a moment-by-moment system.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Picture Sorts results are graphed to visually represent commercial viewers' moment-by-moment image recognition (Flow of Attention), positive and negative feelings (Flow of Emotion), and brand values (Flow of Meaning).
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Trends in in-market tracking include a greater focus on the multimedia nature of entire advertising campaigns.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] 2000s – Global advertisers seek an integrated marketing research system that will work worldwide so they can compare results across countries.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] For a look at trends predicted for advertising research in the 21st century, see Seven Trends for the Future.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Robert Heath publishes the seminal and controversial monograph “The Hidden Power of Advertising” which challenged the traditional models used in advertising research and shows how most advertising is processed at an emotional level (not a rational level).
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] His monograph leads to re-examination of in-market research approaches that compare the behaviors of those who have seen advertising versus those who have not, such as the Communicus System, and the development of brand new pretesting systems such as the OTX AdCEP system.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] There are two types of research, customized and syndicated.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Customized research is conducted for a specific client to address that client’s needs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Only that client has access to the results of the research.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Syndicated research is a single research study conducted by a research company with its results available, for sale, to multiple companies.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Pre-market research can be conducted to optimize advertisements for any medium: radio, television, print (magazine, newspaper or direct mail), outdoor billboard (highway, bus, or train), or Internet.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Different methods would be applied to gather the necessary data appropriately.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Post-testing is conducted after the advertising, either a single ad or an entire multimedia campaign has been run in-market.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] The focus is on what the advertising has done for the brand, for example increasing brand awareness, trial, frequency of purchasing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Pre-testing, also known as copy testing, is a specialized field of marketing research that determines an ad’s effectiveness based on consumer responses, feedback, and behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Pre-testing is conducted before implementing the advertisement to customers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] A new area of pre-testing driven by the realization that what works on TV does not necessarily translate in other media.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Greater budgets allocated to digital media in particular have driven the need for campaign pre-testing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] The addition of a media planning tool to this testing approach allows advertisers to test the whole campaign, creative and media, and measures the synergies expected with an integrated campaign.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Post-testing/Tracking studies provide either periodic or continuous in-market research monitoring a brand’s performance, including brand awareness, brand preference, product usage and attitudes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Some post-testing approaches simply track changes over time, while others use various methods to quantify the specific changes produced by advertising—either the campaign as a whole or by the different media utilized.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Beyond survey-based tracking, causal lift methodologies have gained prominence as advertisers seek evidence of actual behavioral change rather than attitudinal shifts.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Because only experiments, not models, can establish causality, holdout-based lift tests are increasingly regarded as the gold standard against which attribution outputs are calibrated.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Where individual-level randomization is impractical—for example, in linear television, out-of-home, or broad digital campaigns—geo experiments offer a causal alternative by randomly assigning non-overlapping geographic regions to treatment or control conditions and comparing aggregate outcomes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Larsen et al. introduce GeoLift, an open-source framework that uses synthetic control methods to construct a counterfactual for treated regions from a weighted combination of control regions, improving precision when the number of available geos is small.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Overall, advertisers use post-testing to plan future advertising campaigns, so the approaches that provide the most detailed information on the accomplishments of the campaign are most valued.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] With the longitudinal approach, it is possible to go beyond brand awareness, and to isolate the campaign's impact on specific behavioral and perceptual dimensions, and to isolate campaign impact by media.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Attribution models allocate conversion credit across ad exposures using observed user paths rather than experimental manipulation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] These include rules-based systems such as last-touch or first-touch, as well as data-driven multi-touch attribution (MTA).
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Incrementality experiments are randomized holdout tests that compare outcomes for exposed and unexposed groups.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] They offer a causal alternative to attribution, but research has found that they frequently produce estimates that diverge substantially from attribution-based figures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] A subsequent large-scale replication using 663 Facebook experiments confirmed that non-experimental methods continue to overestimate causal effects even when flexible machine-learning estimators are applied.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Google developed geo experiments, in which non-overlapping geographic regions are randomly assigned to treatment or control conditions, as a practical method for obtaining causal estimates of advertising return on investment at scale without individual-level randomization.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Facebook's Conversion Lift product similarly uses randomized test and control groups to isolate incremental conversions attributable to ads.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Meta has recommended using lift results to calibrate attribution models when the two diverge.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] In advertising research, **attention** is the qualitative measure of an advertisement's effectiveness in arousing interest in a viewer.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Qualitative is a measurement that is based on peoples emotions and opinions of the advertisement.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Focus Group based methodologies can be used to collect qualitative responses which inform a measure of attention to an advertisement in a simulated environment.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] One example of this is a "dummy advertising vehicle test," in which a test Television Advertisement is shown with control ads in a controlled environment designed to simulate a commercial break on television.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] The test ad is embedded alongside either directly competitive advertising, or ads from non-competing product categories, depending on the advertiser's preference.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Respondents are asked the question "Which of these ads did you find interesting?" If the test ad is spontaneously mentioned, then that response is counted toward the attention score.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Quantitative techniques such as Eye Tracking are used to measure attention and spontaneous response to marketing messages.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Quantitative measurements are based on data and numbers that are gathered from studies based on how people react to the advertisements .
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Attention data using this methodology can be collected in a variety of simulated environments such as at home or work, as well as across a variety of different screens and devices.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] In addition to measuring attention, this data can be used by advertisers to optimize the design and placement of advertisements.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Advertisers like to make people feel things in order to gain their attention.
[src:nonverbal-communication/advertising-research] Eye-tracking techniques can be measured by observing the eye movement and pupil dilation when looking at an advertisement.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Affect is important in psychology as well as in communication, mostly when it comes to interpersonal communication and non-verbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] In both psychology and communication, there are a multitude of theories that explain affect and its impact on humans and quality of life.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Affect can be taken to indicate an instinctual reaction to stimulation occurring before the typical cognitive processes considered necessary for the formation of a more complex emotion.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Zajonc asserts that this reaction to stimuli is primary for human beings and is the dominant reaction for lower organisms.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Zajonc suggests affective reactions can occur without extensive perceptual and cognitive encoding, and can be made sooner and with greater confidence than cognitive judgments.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Lazarus on the other hand considers affect to be post-cognitive.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] That is, affect is elicited only after a certain amount of cognitive processing of information has been accomplished.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] A divergence from a narrow reinforcement model for emotion allows for other perspectives on how affect influences emotional development.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Thus, temperament, cognitive development, socialization patterns, and the idiosyncrasies of one's family or subculture are mutually interactive in non-linear ways.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] As an example, the temperament of a highly reactive, low self-soothing infant may "disproportionately" affect the process of emotion regulation in the early months of life.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] In relation to perception, a type of non-conscious affect may be separate from the cognitive processing of environmental stimuli.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] A monohierarchy of perception, affect and cognition considers the roles of arousal, attentional tendencies, affective primacy, evolutionary constraints, and covert perception within the sensing and processing of preferences and discrimination.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Emotions are complex chains of events triggered by certain stimuli.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] There is no way to completely describe an emotion by knowing only some of its components.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Verbal reports of feelings are often inaccurate because people may not know exactly what they feel, or they may feel several different emotions at the same time.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] There are also situations that arise in which individuals attempt to hide their feelings, and there are some who believe that public and private events seldom coincide exactly, and that words for feelings are generally more ambiguous than are words for objects or events.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Affective responses, on the other hand, are more basic and may be less problematic in terms of assessment.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] (requiring) minimal attention to occur and...
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] (capable of being) activated without intention or awareness" (1989 p.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Arousal is a basic physiological response to the presentation of stimuli.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] When this occurs, a non-conscious affective process takes the form of two control mechanisms; one mobilization, and the other immobilization.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Within the human brain, the amygdala regulates an instinctual reaction initiating this arousal process, either freezing the individual or accelerating mobilization.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] The arousal response is illustrated in studies focused on reward systems that control food-seeking behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Researchers focused on learning processes and modulatory processes that are present while encoding and retrieving goal values.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] When an organism seeks food, the anticipation of reward based on environmental events becomes another influence on food seeking that is separate from the reward of food itself.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Therefore, earning the reward and anticipating the reward are separate processes and both create an excitatory influence of reward-related cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Both processes are dissociated at the level of the amygdala and are functionally integrated within larger neural systems.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Mood, like emotion, is an affective state.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] However, an emotion tends to have a clear focus (i.e., a self-evident cause), while mood tends to be more unfocused and diffused.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Mood, according to Batson, Shaw, and Oleson (1992), involves tone and intensity and a structured set of beliefs about general expectations of a future experience of pleasure or pain, or of positive or negative affect in the future.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Unlike instant reactions that produce affect or emotion, and that change with expectations of future pleasure or pain, moods, being diffused and unfocused, and thus harder to cope with, can last for days, weeks, months, or even years.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Moods are hypothetical constructs depicting an individual's emotional state.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Researchers typically infer the existence of moods from a variety of behavioral referents.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Positive affect and negative affect represent independent domains of emotion in the general population, and positive affect is strongly linked to social interaction.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Positive and negative daily events show independent relationships to subjective well-being, and positive affect is strongly linked to social activity.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Recent research suggests that "high functional support is related to higher levels of positive affect".
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] The exact process through which social support is linked to positive affect remains unclear.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] The process could derive from predictable, regularized social interaction, from leisure activities where the focus is on relaxation and positive mood, or from the enjoyment of shared activities.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Research has indicated many differences in affective displays due to gender.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Gender, as opposed to sex, is one's self-perception of being masculine or feminine (i.e., a male can perceive himself to be more feminine or a female can perceive herself to be more masculine).
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] It can also be argued, however, that hormones (typically determined by sex) greatly affect affective displays and mood.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] According to studies done in the late '80s and early '90s, infants within their first year of life are not only able to begin recognizing affect displays but can begin mimicking the displays and also begin developing empathy.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] A study in 2011 followed up on these earlier studies by testing fifteen 6-12 month old infants' arousal, via pupil dilation, when looking at both positive and negative displays.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Results showed that when presented with negative affect, an infant's pupil will dilate and stay dilated for a longer period of time when compared to neutral affect.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] When presented with positive affect however, the pupil dilation is much larger, but stays dilated for shorter amount of time.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] While this study does not prove an infant's ability to empathize with others, it does show that infants do recognize and acknowledge both positive and negative displays of emotion.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] In the early 2000s over the period of about seven years, a study was done on about 200 children whose mother had "a history of juvenile-onset unipolar depressive disorder" or simply, depression as children themselves.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] In the cases of unipolar depression, a person generally displays more negative affect and less positive affect than a person without depression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Or, they are more likely to show when they are sad or upset, than when they are excited or happy.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] This study that was published in 2010 discovered that the children of mothers that have unipolar depression, had lower levels of positive affect when compared to the control group.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Even as the children grew older, while the negative affect began to stay the same, the children still showed consistently lower positive affect.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] This study suggests that "Reduced PA [positive affect] may be one source of developmental vulnerability to familial depression..." meaning that while having family with depression, increases the risk of children developing depression, reduced positive affect increases the risk of this development.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] But knowing this aspect of depression, might also be able to help prevent the onset of depression in young children well into their adulthood.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] There are some diseases, physical disabilities and mental health disorders that can change the way a person's affect displays are conveyed.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Reduced affect is when a person's emotions cannot be properly conveyed or displayed physically.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] There is no actual change in how intensely they truly feel emotions; there is simply a disparity between emotions felt and how intensely they are conveyed.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] These disorders can greatly affect a person's quality of life, depending on how intense the disability is.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Flat, blunted, and restricted affects refer to a pattern in which an affected person feels an emotion but does not or cannot display it.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] A flat affect is the most severe case in which there is little to no display of emotions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Restricted and blunted affects are less severe.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Disorders involving these reduced affect displays most commonly include schizophrenia, post traumatic stress disorder, depression, autism and traumatic brain injuries.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] One study has shown that people with schizophrenia that experience flat affect can also experience difficulty perceiving the emotions of a healthy individual.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] People who have facial deformities or paralysis may also be physically incapable of displaying emotions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] This is beginning to be corrected though, through "Facial Reanimation Surgery" which is proving not only to successfully improve a patient's affect displays, but also bettering their psychological health.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] There are multiple types of surgeries that can help fix facial paralysis.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Emotions can be displayed in order to elicit desired behaviors from others.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] People have been known to display positive emotions in various settings.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Service workers often engage in emotional labor, a strive to maintain positive emotional expressions despite difficulties in working conditions or rude customers, in order to conform to organizational rules.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Such strategic displays are not always effective, since if they are detected, lower customer satisfaction results.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Perhaps the most notable attempt to feign negative emotion could be seen with Nixon's madman theory.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Nixon's administration attempted to make the leaders of other countries think Nixon was mad, and that his behavior was irrational and volatile.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Fearing an unpredictable American response, leaders of hostile Communist Bloc nations would avoid provoking the United States.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] This diplomatic strategy was not ultimately successful.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] The effectiveness of the strategic display depends on the ability of the expresser to remain undetected.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] It may be a risky strategy since, if detected, the person's original intent could be discovered, undermining the future relationship with the target.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] According to the appraisal theory of emotions, the experience of emotions is preceded by an evaluation of an object of significance to that individual.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] When individuals are seen to display emotions, it serves as a signal to others of an event important to that individual.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] Thus, deliberately altering the emotion display toward an object could be used make the targets of the strategic emotion think and behave in ways that benefit the original expresser.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-display] For example, people attempt to hide their expressions during a poker game in order to avoid giving away information to the other players, i.e., keep a poker face.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] In linguistics, **affect** is an attitude or emotion that a speaker brings to an utterance.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] Lexical choices may frame a speaker's affect, such as *slender* (positive affect) vs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] *scrawny* (negative affect), *thrifty* (positive) vs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] *stingy* (negative) and *freedom fighter* (positive) vs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] In many languages of Europe, augmentative derivations are used to express contempt or other negative attitudes toward the noun being so modified, whereas diminutives may express affection; on the other hand, diminutives are frequently used to belittle or be dismissive.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] For instance, in Spanish, a name ending in diminutive *-ito* (masculine) or *-ita* (feminine) may be a term of endearment, but *señorito* "little mister" for *señor* "mister" may be mocking.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] Polish has a range of augmentative and diminutive forms, which express differences in affect.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] So, from *żaba* "a frog", besides *żabucha* for simply a big frog, there is augmentative *żabsko* to express distaste, *żabisko* if the frog is ugly, *żabula* if it is likeably awkward, etc.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] Affect can also be conveyed by more subtle means.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] Duranti, for example, shows that the use of pronouns in Italian narration indicates that the character referred to is important to the narration but is generally also a mark of a positive speaker attitude toward the character.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] In Japanese and Korean, grammatical affect is conveyed both through honorific, polite, and humble language, which affects both nouns and verbal inflection, and through clause-final particles that express a range of speaker emotions and attitudes toward what is being said.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] ʔaː=tʼo béda=ht̪ow béː=yo-w dá-ːʔ-du-w tʃʰó-w. béda ʔaː qʼlá-w=ʔkʰe.
[src:nonverbal-communication/affect-linguistics] "(But) I don't want to go away from here.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In definitions commonly used in the social sciences and behavioral sciences, aggression is an action or response by an individual that delivers something unpleasant to another person.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Some definitions include that the individual must intend to harm another person.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In an interdisciplinary perspective, aggression is regarded as "an ensemble of mechanisms formed during the course of evolution in order to assert oneself, relatives, or friends against others, to gain or to defend resources (ultimate causes) by harmful damaging means.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] These mechanisms are often motivated by emotions such as fear, frustration, anger, stress, dominance or pleasure (proximate causes).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Sometimes aggressive behavior serves as a stress relief or a subjective feeling of power." Predatory or defensive behavior between members of different species may not be considered aggression in the same sense.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] There are two subtypes of human aggression: (1) controlled-instrumental subtype (purposeful or goal-oriented); and (2) reactive-impulsive subtype (often elicits uncontrollable actions that are inappropriate or undesirable).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression differs from what is commonly called assertiveness, although the terms are often used interchangeably among laypeople (as in phrases such as "an aggressive salesperson").
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] (1939) proposed that aggression was due to frustration, which was described as an unpleasant emotion resulting from any interference with achieving a rewarding goal.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Berkowitz extended this frustration–aggression hypothesis and proposed that it is not so much the frustration as the unpleasant emotion that evokes aggressive tendencies, and that all aversive events produce negative affect and thereby aggressive tendencies, as well as fear tendencies.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression can have adaptive benefits or negative effects.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggressive behavior is an individual or collective social interaction that is a hostile behavior with the intention of inflicting damage or harm.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Two broad categories of aggression are commonly distinguished.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] One includes affective (emotional) and hostile, reactive, or retaliatory aggression that is a response to provocation, and the other includes instrumental, goal-oriented or predatory, in which aggression is used as a means to achieve a goal.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] An example of hostile aggression would be a person who punches someone that insulted him or her.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] An instrumental form of aggression would be armed robbery.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Research on violence from a range of disciplines lend some support to a distinction between affective and predatory aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, some researchers question the usefulness of a hostile versus instrumental distinction in humans, despite its ubiquity in research, because most real-life cases involve mixed motives and interacting causes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] A number of classifications and dimensions of aggression have been suggested.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Classification may also encompass aggression-related emotions (e.g., anger) and mental states (e.g., impulsivity, hostility).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression may occur in response to non-social as well as social factors, and can have a close relationship with stress coping style.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression may be displayed in order to intimidate.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The operative definition of aggression may be affected by moral or political views.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Examples are the axiomatic moral view called the non-aggression principle and the political rules governing the behavior of one country toward another.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Likewise in competitive sports, or in the workplace, some forms of aggression may be sanctioned and others not (see Workplace aggression).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggressive behaviors are associated with adjustment problems and several psychopathological symptoms such as antisocial personality disorder, borderline personality disorder, and intermittent explosive disorder.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Biological approaches conceptualize aggression as an internal energy released by external stimuli, a product of evolution through natural selection, part of genetics, and a product of hormonal fluctuations.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Psychological approaches conceptualize aggression as a destructive instinct, a response to frustration, an affect excited by a negative stimulus, a result of observed learning of society and diversified reinforcement, and a result of variables that affect personal and situational environments.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The term aggression comes from the Latin word *aggressio*, meaning attack.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The Latin was itself a joining of *ad*- and *gradi*-, which meant "step at".
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The first known use dates back to 1611, in the sense of an unprovoked attack.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] A psychological sense of "hostile or destructive behavior" dates back to a 1912 English translation of Sigmund Freud's writing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Alfred Adler theorized about an "aggressive drive" in 1908.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Child raising experts began to refer to aggression, rather than anger, from the 1930s.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Ethologists study aggression as it relates to the interaction and evolution of animals in natural settings.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In such settings aggression can involve bodily contact such as biting, hitting or pushing, but most conflicts are settled by threat displays and intimidating thrusts that cause no physical harm.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This form of aggression may include the display of body size, antlers, claws or teeth; stereotyped signals including facial expressions; vocalizations such as bird song; the release of chemicals; and changes in coloration.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The term agonistic behavior is sometimes used to refer to these forms of behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Most ethologists believe that aggression confers biological advantages.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression may help an animal secure territory, including resources such as food and water.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression between males often occurs to secure mating opportunities, and results in selection of the healthier/more vigorous animal.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression may also occur for self-protection or to protect offspring.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression between groups of animals may also confer advantage; for example, hostile behavior may force a population of animals into a new territory, where the need to adapt to a new environment may lead to an increase in genetic flexibility.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The most apparent type of interspecific aggression is that observed in the interaction between a predator and its prey.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, according to many researchers, predation is not aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] A cat does not hiss or arch its back when pursuing a rat, and the active areas in its hypothalamus resemble those that reflect hunger rather than those that reflect aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, others refer to this behavior as predatory aggression, and point out cases that resemble hostile behavior, such as mouse-killing by rats.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In aggressive mimicry a predator has the appearance of a harmless organism or object attractive to the prey; when the prey approaches, the predator attacks.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] An animal defending against a predator may engage in either "fight or flight" or "tend and befriend" in response to predator attack or threat of attack, depending on its estimate of the predator's strength relative to its own.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Alternative defenses include a range of antipredator adaptations, including alarm signals.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] An example of an alarm signal is Nerol, a chemical which is found in the mandibular glands of *Trigona fulviventris* individuals.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Release of Nerol by T. fulviventris individuals in the nest has been shown to decrease the number of individuals leaving the nest by fifty percent, as well as increasing aggressive behaviors like biting.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Alarm signals like nerol can also act as attraction signals; in T. fulviventris, individuals that have been captured by a predator may release nerol to attract nest mates, who will proceed to attack or bite the predator.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Also, an individual is more likely to become aggressive if other aggressive group members are nearby.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] One particular phenomenon – the formation of coordinated coalitions that raid neighboring territories to kill conspecifics – has only been documented in two species in the animal kingdom: 'common' chimpanzees and humans.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression between conspecifics in a group typically involves access to resources and breeding opportunities.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] One of its most common functions is to establish a dominance hierarchy.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This occurs in many species by aggressive encounters between contending males when they are first together in a common environment.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Usually the more aggressive animals become the more dominant.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In test situations, most of the conspecific aggression ceases about 24 hours after the group of animals is brought together.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression has been defined from this viewpoint as "behavior which is intended to increase the social dominance of the organism relative to the dominance position of other organisms".
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Losing confrontations may be called social defeat, and winning or losing is associated with a range of practical and psychological consequences.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Conflicts between animals occur in many contexts, such as between potential mating partners, between parents and offspring, between siblings and between competitors for resources.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Group-living animals may dispute over the direction of travel or the allocation of time to joint activities.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Various factors limit the escalation of aggression, including communicative displays, conventions, and routines.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In addition, following aggressive incidents, various forms of conflict resolution have been observed in mammalian species, particularly in gregarious primates.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] These can mitigate or repair possible adverse consequences, especially for the recipient of aggression who may become vulnerable to attacks by other members of a group.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Conciliatory acts vary by species and may involve specific gestures or simply more proximity and interaction between the individuals involved.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, conflicts over food are rarely followed by post conflict reunions, even though they are the most frequent type in foraging primates.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Other questions that have been considered in the study of primate aggression, including in humans, is how aggression affects the organization of a group, what costs are incurred by aggression, and why some primates avoid aggressive behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] For example, bonobo chimpanzee groups are known for low levels of aggression within a partially matriarchal society.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Captive animals including primates may show abnormal levels of social aggression and self-harm that are related to aspects of the physical or social environment; this depends on the species and individual factors such as gender, age and background (e.g., raised wild or captive).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Within ethology, it has long been recognized that there is a relation between aggression, fear, and curiosity.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In this approach, when the inconsistency between perception and expectancy is small, learning as a result of curiosity reduces inconsistency by updating expectancy to match perception.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] If the inconsistency is larger, fear or aggressive behavior may be employed to alter the perception in order to make it match expectancy, depending on the size of the inconsistency as well as the specific context.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Uninhibited fear results in fleeing, thereby removing the inconsistent stimulus from the perceptual field and resolving the inconsistency.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In some cases, thwarted escape may trigger aggressive behavior in an attempt to remove the thwarting stimulus.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Like many behaviors, aggression can be examined in terms of its ability to help an animal itself survive and reproduce, or alternatively to risk survival and reproduction.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This cost–benefit analysis can be looked at in terms of evolution.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, there are profound differences in the extent of acceptance of a biological or evolutionary basis for human aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression can involve violence that may be adaptive under certain circumstances in terms of natural selection.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This is most obviously the case in terms of attacking prey to obtain food, or in anti-predatory defense.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] It may also be the case in competition between members of the same species or subgroup, if the average reward (e.g., status, access to resources, protection of self or kin) outweighs average costs (e.g., injury, exclusion from the group, death).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] There are some hypotheses of specific adaptions for violence in humans under certain circumstances, including for homicide, but it is often unclear what behaviors may have been selected for and what may have been a byproduct, as in the case of collective violence.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Although aggressive encounters are ubiquitous in the animal kingdom, with often high stakes, most encounters that involve aggression may be resolved through posturing, or displaying and trial of strength.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Game theory is used to understand how such behaviors might spread by natural selection within a population, and potentially become 'Evolutionary Stable Strategies'.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] An initial model of resolution of conflicts is the hawk-dove game.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Others include the Sequential assessment model and the Energetic war of attrition.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] These try to understand not just one-off encounters but protracted stand-offs, and mainly differ in the criteria by which an individual decides to give up rather than risk loss and harm in physical conflict (such as through estimates of resource holding potential).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Gender plays an important role in human aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] There are multiple theories that seek to explain findings that males and females of the same species can have differing aggressive behaviors.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] One review concluded that male aggression tended to produce pain or physical injury, whereas female aggression tended towards psychological or social harm.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In general, sexual dimorphism can be attributed to greater intraspecific competition in one sex, either between rivals for access to mates and/or to be chosen by mates.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This may stem from the other gender being constrained by providing greater parental investment, in terms of factors such as gamete production, gestation, lactation, or upbringing of young.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Although there is much variation in species, generally the more physically aggressive sex is the male, particularly in mammals.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In species where parental care by both sexes is required, there tends to be less of a difference.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] When the female can leave the male to care for the offspring, then females may be the larger and more physically aggressive.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Competitiveness despite parental investment has also been observed in some species.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] A related factor is the rate at which males and females are able to mate again after producing offspring, and the basic principles of sexual selection are also influenced by ecological factors affecting the ways or extent to which one sex can compete for the other.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The role of such factors in human evolution is controversial.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The pattern of male and female aggression is argued to be consistent with evolved sexually selected behavioral differences, while alternative or complementary views emphasize conventional social roles stemming from physical evolved differences.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggression in women may have evolved to be, on average, less physically dangerous and more covert or indirect.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, there are critiques of using animal behavior to explain human behavior, especially in the application of evolutionary explanations to contemporary human behavior, including differences between genders.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] According to the 2015 *International Encyclopedia of the Social & Behavioral Sciences*, sex differences in aggression is one of the most robust and oldest findings in psychology.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Past meta-analyses in the encyclopedia found males regardless of age engaged in more physical and verbal aggression while small effect for females engaging in more indirect aggression such as rumor spreading or gossiping.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] It also found males tend to engage in more unprovoked aggression at higher frequency than females.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This analysis also conforms with the *Oxford Handbook of Evolutionary Psychology* which reviewed past analysis which found men to use more verbal and physical aggression with the difference being greater in the physical type.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] There are more recent findings that show that differences in male and female aggression appear at about two years of age, though the differences in aggression are more consistent in middle-aged children and adolescence.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Tremblay, Japel and Pérusse (1999) asserted that physically aggressive behaviors such as kicking, biting and hitting are age-typical expressions of innate and spontaneous reactions to biological drives such as anger, hunger, and affiliation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Girls' relational aggression, meaning non-physical or indirect, tends to increase after age two while physical aggression decreases.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] There was no significant difference in aggression between males and females before two years of age.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] A possible explanation for this could be that girls develop language skills more quickly than boys, and therefore have better ways of verbalizing their wants and needs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] According to the journal of *Aggressive Behaviour*, an analysis across 9 countries found boys reported more in the use of physical aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] At the same time no consistent sex differences emerged within relational aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] It has been found that girls are more likely than boys to use reactive aggression and then retract, but boys are more likely to increase rather than to retract their aggression after their first reaction.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Studies show girls' aggressive tactics included gossip, ostracism, breaking confidences, and criticism of a victim's clothing, appearance, or personality, whereas boys engage in aggression that involves a direct physical and/or verbal assault.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This could be due to the fact that girls' frontal lobes develop earlier than boys, allowing them to self-restrain.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] One factor that shows insignificant differences between male and female aggression is in sports.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In sports, the rate of aggression in both contact and non-contact sports is relatively equal.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Since the establishment of Title IX, female sports have increased in competitiveness and importance, which could contribute to the evening of aggression and the "need to win" attitude between both genders.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Among sex differences found in adult sports were that females have a higher scale of indirect hostility while men have a higher scale of assault.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Another difference found is that men have up to 20 times higher levels of testosterone than women.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Some studies suggest that romantic involvement in adolescence decreases aggression in males and females, but decreases at a higher rate in females.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Females will seem more desirable to their mate if they fit in with society and females that are aggressive do not usually fit well in society.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Female aggression is not considered the norm in society and going against the norm can sometimes prevent one from getting a mate.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, studies have shown that an increasing number of women are getting arrested on domestic violence charges.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In many states, women now account for a quarter to a third of all domestic violence arrests, up from less than 10 percent a decade ago.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The new statistics reflect a reality documented in research: women are perpetrators as well as victims of family violence.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, another equally possible explanation is a case of improved diagnostics: it has become more acceptable for men to report female domestic violence to the authorities while at the same time actual female domestic violence has not increased at all.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This could be the case in a situation where men had become less ashamed of reporting female violence against them⁠‍—‍such a situation could conceivably lead to an increasing number of women being arrested despite the actual number of violent women remaining the same.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In addition, males in competitive sports are often advised by their coaches not to be in intimate relationships based on the premise that they become more docile and less aggressive during an athletic event.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The circumstances in which males and females experience aggression are also different.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] A study showed that social anxiety and stress were positively correlated with aggression in males, meaning that as stress and social anxiety increase, so does aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Furthermore, a male with higher social skills has a lower rate of aggressive behavior than a male with lower social skills.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In females, higher rates of aggression were only correlated with higher rates of stress.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Other than biological factors that contribute to aggression, there are physical factors as well.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Regarding sexual dimorphism, humans fall into an intermediate group with moderate sex differences in body size but relatively large testes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This is a typical pattern of primates where several males and females live together in a group and the male faces an intermediate number of challenges from other males compared to exclusive polygyny and monogamy but frequent sperm competition.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Evolutionary psychology and sociobiology have also discussed and produced theories for some specific forms of male aggression such as sociobiological theories of rape and theories regarding the Cinderella effect.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Many researchers focus on the brain to explain aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Numerous circuits within both neocortical and subcortical structures play a central role in controlling aggressive behavior, depending on the species, and the exact role of pathways may vary depending on the type of trigger or intention.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In mammals, the hypothalamus and periaqueductal gray of the midbrain are critical areas, as shown in studies on cats, rats, and monkeys.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] These brain areas control the expression of both behavioral and autonomic components of aggression in these species, including vocalization.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Electrical stimulation of the hypothalamus causes aggressive behavior and the hypothalamus has receptors that help determine aggression levels based on their interactions with serotonin and vasopressin.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In rodents, activation of estrogen receptor-expressing neurons in the ventrolateral portion of the ventromedial hypothalamus (VMHvl) was found to be sufficient to initiate aggression in both males and females.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Midbrain areas involved in aggression have direct connections with both the brainstem nuclei controlling these functions, and with structures such as the amygdala and prefrontal cortex.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Stimulation of the amygdala results in augmented aggressive behavior in hamsters, while lesions of an evolutionarily homologous area in the lizard greatly reduce competitive drive and aggression (Bauman et al.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In rhesus monkeys, neonatal lesions in the amygdala or hippocampus results in reduced expression of social dominance, related to the regulation of aggression and fear.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Several experiments in attack-primed Syrian golden hamsters, for example, support the claim of circuitry within the amygdala being involved in control of aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The role of the amygdala is less clear in primates and appears to depend more on situational context, with lesions leading to increases in either social affiliatory or aggressive responses.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Amygdalotomy, which involves removing or destroying parts of the amygdala, has been performed on people to reduce their violent behaviour.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The broad area of the cortex known as the prefrontal cortex (PFC) is crucial for self-control and inhibition of impulses, including inhibition of aggression and emotions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Reduced activity of the prefrontal cortex, in particular its medial and orbitofrontal portions, has been associated with violent/antisocial aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In addition, reduced response inhibition has been found in violent offenders, compared to non-violent offenders.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The role of the chemicals in the brain, particularly neurotransmitters, in aggression has also been examined.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This varies depending on the pathway, the context and other factors such as gender.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] A deficit in serotonin has been theorized to have a primary role in causing impulsivity and aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] At least one epigenetic study supports this supposition.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Nevertheless, low levels of serotonin transmission may explain a vulnerability to impulsiveness, potential aggression, and may have an effect through interactions with other neurochemical systems.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] These include dopamine systems which are generally associated with attention and motivation toward rewards, and operate at various levels.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Norepinephrine, also known as noradrenaline, may influence aggression responses both directly and indirectly through the hormonal system, the sympathetic nervous system or the central nervous system (including the brain).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] It appears to have different effects depending on the type of triggering stimulus, for example social isolation/rank versus shock/chemical agitation which appears not to have a linear relationship with aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Similarly, GABA, although associated with inhibitory functions at many CNS synapses, sometimes shows a positive correlation with aggression, including when potentiated by alcohol.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The hormonal neuropeptides vasopressin and oxytocin play a key role in complex social behaviours in many mammals such as regulating attachment, social recognition, and aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Vasopressin has been implicated in male-typical social behaviors which includes aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Oxytocin may have a particular role in regulating female bonds with offspring and mates, including the use of protective aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Initial studies in humans suggest some similar effects.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In human, aggressive behavior has been associated with abnormalities in three principal regulatory systems in the body serotonin systems, catecholamine systems, and the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Early androgenization has an organizational effect on the developing brains of both males and females, making more neural circuits that control sexual behavior as well as intermale and interfemale aggression become more sensitive to testosterone.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] There are noticeable sex differences in aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Testosterone is present to a lesser extent in females, who may be more sensitive to its effects.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Animal studies have also indicated a link between incidents of aggression and the individual level of circulating testosterone.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, results in relation to primates, particularly humans, are less clear cut and are at best only suggestive of a positive association in some contexts.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In humans, there is a seasonal variation in aggression associated with changes in testosterone.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] For example, in some primate species, such as rhesus monkeys and baboons, females are more likely to engage in fights around the time of ovulation as well as right before menstruation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] If the results were the same in humans as they are in rhesus monkeys and baboons, then the increase in aggressive behaviors during ovulation is explained by the decline in estrogen levels.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This makes normal testosterone levels more effective.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Castrated mice and rats exhibit lower levels of aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Males castrated as neonates exhibit low levels of aggression even when given testosterone throughout their development.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The challenge hypothesis outlines the dynamic relationship between plasma testosterone levels and aggression in mating contexts in many species.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] It proposes that testosterone is linked to aggression when it is beneficial for reproduction, such as in mate guarding and preventing the encroachment of intrasexual rivals.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The challenge hypothesis predicts that seasonal patterns in testosterone levels in a species are a function of mating system (monogamy versus polygyny), paternal care, and male-male aggression in seasonal breeders.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This pattern between testosterone and aggression was first observed in seasonally breeding birds, such as the song sparrow, where testosterone levels rise modestly with the onset of the breeding season to support basic reproductive functions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The hypothesis has been subsequently expanded and modified to predict relationships between testosterone and aggression in other species.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] For example, chimpanzees, which are continuous breeders, show significantly raised testosterone levels and aggressive male-male interactions when receptive and fertile females are present.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Currently, no research has specified a relationship between the modified challenge hypothesis and human behavior, or the human nature of concealed ovulation, although some suggest it may apply.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Another line of research has focused on the proximate effects of circulating testosterone on the nervous system, as mediated by local metabolism within the brain.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Testosterone can be metabolized to estradiol by the enzyme aromatase, or to dihydrotestosterone (DHT) by 5α-reductase.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aromatase is highly expressed in regions involved in the regulation of aggressive behavior, such as the amygdala and hypothalamus.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In studies using genetic knockout techniques in inbred mice, male mice that lacked a functional aromatase enzyme displayed a marked reduction in aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Long-term treatment with estradiol partially restored aggressive behavior, suggesting that the neural conversion of circulating testosterone to estradiol and its effect on estrogen receptors influences inter-male aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In addition, two different estrogen receptors, ERα and ERβ, have been identified as having the ability to exert different effects on aggression in mice.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, the effect of estradiol appears to vary depending on the strain of mouse, and in some strains it reduces aggression during long days (16 h of light), while during short days (8 h of light) estradiol rapidly increases aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Another hypothesis is that testosterone influences brain areas that control behavioral reactions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Studies in animal models indicate that aggression is affected by several interconnected cortical and subcortical structures within the so-called social behavior network.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] A study involving lesions and electrical-chemical stimulation in rodents and cats revealed that such a neural network consists of the medial amygdala, medial hypothalamus and periaqueductal grey (PAG), and it positively modulates reactive aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Moreover, a study done in human subjects showed that prefrontal-amygdala connectivity is modulated by endogenous testosterone during social emotional behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In human studies, testosterone-aggression research has also focused on the role of the orbitofrontal cortex (OFC).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This brain area is strongly associated with impulse control and self-regulation systems that integrate emotion, motivation, and cognition to guide context-appropriate behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Patients with localized lesions to the OFC engage in heightened reactive aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Aggressive behavior may be regulated by testosterone via reduced medial OFC engagement following social provocation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] When measuring participants' salivary testosterone, higher levels can predict subsequent aggressive behavioral reactions to unfairness faced during a task.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Moreover, brain scanning with fMRI shows reduced activity in the medial OFC during such reactions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Such findings may suggest that a specific brain region, the OFC, is a key factor in understanding reactive aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Scientists have for a long time been interested in the relationship between testosterone and aggressive behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In most species, males are more aggressive than females.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Castration of males usually has a pacifying effect on aggressive behavior in males.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In humans, males engage in crime and especially violent crime more than females.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The involvement in crime usually rises in the early teens to mid teens which happen at the same time as testosterone levels rise.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Research on the relationship between testosterone and aggression is difficult since the only reliable measurement of brain testosterone is by a lumbar puncture which is not done for research purposes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Studies therefore have often instead used more unreliable measurements from blood or saliva.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] No specific response of testosterone levels to competition was observed in female athletes, although a mood difference was noted.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In addition, some experiments have failed to find a relationship between testosterone levels and aggression in humans.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The possible correlation between testosterone and aggression could explain the "roid rage" that can result from anabolic steroid use, although an effect of abnormally high levels of steroids does not prove an effect at physiological levels.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) is the most abundant circulating androgen hormone and can be rapidly metabolized within target tissues into potent androgens and estrogens.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Gonadal steroids generally regulate aggression during the breeding season, but non-gonadal steroids may regulate aggression during the non-breeding season.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Castration of various species in the non-breeding season has no effect on territorial aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In several avian studies, circulating DHEA has been found to be elevated in birds during the non-breeding season.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] These data support the idea that non-breeding birds combine adrenal and/or gonadal DHEA synthesis with neural DHEA metabolism to maintain territorial behavior when gonadal testosterone secretion is low.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Similar results have been found in studies involving different strains of rats, mice, and hamsters.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] DHEA levels also have been studied in humans and may play a role in human aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Circulating DHEAS (its sulfated ester) levels rise during adrenarche (≈7 years of age) while plasma testosterone levels are relatively low.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] This implies that aggression in pre-pubertal children with aggressive conduct disorder might be correlated with plasma DHEAS rather than plasma testosterone, suggesting an important link between DHEAS and human aggressive behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Glucocorticoid hormones have an important role in regulating aggressive behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In adult rats, acute injections of corticosterone promote aggressive behavior, and acute reduction of corticosterone decreases aggression; however, chronic reduction of corticosterone levels can produce abnormally aggressive behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In addition, glucocorticoids affect the development of aggression and the establishment of social hierarchies.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Adult mice with low baseline levels of corticosterone are more likely to become dominant than mice with high baseline corticosterone levels.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Glucocorticoids are released by the hypothalamic pituitary adrenal (HPA) axis in response to stress, of which cortisol is the most prominent in humans.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Results in adults suggest that reduced levels of cortisol, linked to lower fear or a reduced stress response, can be associated with more aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, it may be that proactive aggression is associated with low cortisol levels while reactive aggression may be accompanied by elevated levels.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Differences in assessments of cortisol may also explain a diversity of results, particularly in children.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The HPA axis is related to the general fight-or-flight response or acute stress reaction, and the role of catecholamines such as epinephrine, popularly known as adrenaline.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In many animals, aggression can be linked to pheromones released between conspecifics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In mice, major urinary proteins (Mups) have been demonstrated to promote innate aggressive behavior in males, and can be mediated by neuromodulatory systems.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Mups activate olfactory sensory neurons in the vomeronasal organ (VNO), a subsystem of the nose known to detect pheromones via specific sensory receptors, of mice and rats.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Pheremones have also been identified in fruit flies, detected by neurons in the antenna, that send a message to the brain eliciting aggression; it has been noted that aggression pheremones have not been identified in humans.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In general, differences in a continuous phenotype such as aggression are likely to result from the action of a large number of genes, each of small effect, which interact with each other and the environment through development and life.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In a non-mammalian example of genes related to aggression, the fruitless gene in fruit flies is a critical determinant of certain sexually dimorphic behaviors, and its artificial alteration can result in a reversal of stereotypically male and female patterns of aggression in fighting.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, in what was thought to be a relatively clear case, inherent complexities have been reported in deciphering the connections between interacting genes in an environmental context and a social phenotype involving multiple behavioral and sensory interactions with another organism.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In mice, candidate genes for differentiating aggression between the sexes are the Sry (sex determining region Y) gene, located on the Y chromosome and the Sts (steroid sulfatase) gene.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The Sts gene encodes the steroid sulfatase enzyme, which is pivotal in the regulation of neurosteroid biosynthesis.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] It is expressed in both sexes, is correlated with levels of aggression among male mice, and increases dramatically in females after parturition and during lactation, corresponding to the onset of maternal aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] At least one study has found a possible epigenetic signature (i.e., decreased methylation at a specific CpG site on the promoter region) of the serotonin receptor 5-HT3a that is associated with maternal aggression among human subjects.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Mice with experimentally elevated sensitivity to oxidative stress (through inhibition of copper-zinc superoxide dismutase, SOD1 activity) were tested for aggressive behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Males completely deficient in SOD1 were found to be more aggressive than both wild-type males and males that express 50% of this antioxidant enzyme.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] They were also faster to attack another male.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The causal connection between SOD1 deficiency and increased aggression is not yet understood.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In humans, there is good evidence that the basic human neural architecture underpinning the potential for flexible aggressive responses is influenced by genes as well as environment.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] In terms of variation between individual people, more than 100 twin and adoption studies have been conducted in recent decades examining the genetic basis of aggressive behavior and related constructs such as conduct disorders.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] According to a meta-analysis published in 2002, approximately 40% of variation between individuals is explained by differences in genes, and 60% by differences in environment (mainly non-shared environmental influences rather than those that would be shared by being raised together).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] However, such studies have depended on self-report or observation by others including parents, which complicates interpretation of the results.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The few laboratory-based analyses have not found significant amounts of individual variation in aggression explicable by genetic variation in the human population.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] Furthermore, linkage and association studies that seek to identify specific genes, for example that influence neurotransmitter or hormone levels, have generally resulted in contradictory findings characterized by failed attempts at replication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] The generally unclear picture has been compared to equally difficult findings obtained in regard to other complex behavioral phenotypes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p01] For example, both 7R and 5R, ADHD-linked VNTR alleles of dopamine receptor D4 gene are directly associated with the incidence of proactive aggression in the men with no history of ADHD.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Humans share aspects of aggression with non-human animals, and have specific aspects and complexity related to factors such as genetics, early development, social learning and flexibility, culture and morals.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Konrad Lorenz stated in his 1963 classic, *On Aggression,* that human behavior is shaped by four main, survival-seeking animal drives.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Taken together, these drives—hunger, fear, reproduction, and aggression—achieve natural selection.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Wilson elaborated in *On Human Nature* that aggression is, typically, a means of gaining control over resources.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Aggression is, thus, aggravated during times when high population densities generate resource shortages.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] According to Richard Leakey and his colleagues, aggression in humans has also increased by becoming more interested in ownership and by defending his or her property.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] However, UNESCO adopted the Seville Statement of Violence in 1989 that refuted claims, by evolutionary scientists, that genetics by itself was the sole cause of aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Social and cultural aspects may significantly interfere with the distinct expression of aggressiveness.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] For example, a high population density, when associated with a decrease of available resources, might be a significant intervening variable for the occurrence of violent acts.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Culture is one of the factors that influence aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Tribal or band societies existing before or outside of modern states have sometimes been depicted as peaceful "noble savages".
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The ǃKung people, for instance, were described as "The Harmless People" in a popular work by Elizabeth Marshall Thomas in 1958.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] However, Lawrence Keeley's 1996 War Before Civilization suggested that regular warfare without modern technology was conducted by most groups throughout human history, including most Native American tribes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Research on hunter-gatherers has revealed a range of behavioral patterns.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] While aggression, conflict and violence can occur, direct confrontation is generally avoided, and disputes are often managed through various verbal and non-verbal social mechanisms.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Different rates of aggression or violence—whether contemporary or historical—have been associated with social structures and environmental factors such as resource distribution or property acquisition, land use, subsistence strategies, and population dynamics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Gray likens hunter-gatherer bands to social play groups, while stressing that such play is not frivolous or even easy at all times.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] According to Gray, "Social play—that is, play involving more than one player—is necessarily egalitarian.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] It always requires a suspension of aggression and dominance along with a heightened sensitivity to the needs and desires of the other players".
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Joan Durrant of the University of Manitoba reports that multiple studies have found an association between physical punishment and higher levels of aggression directed toward parents, siblings, peers, and spouses, even when controlling for other influencing factors.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Similarly, Elizabeth Gershoff of the University of Texas at Austin has found that the more frequently children experience physical punishment, the more likely they are, as adults, to engage in violent behavior toward family members, including intimate partners.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] In countries where the physical punishment of children is more culturally accepted, its association with increased aggression tends to be weaker.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] However, research indicates that physical punishment predicts some increase in child aggression regardless of cultural context.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Although these associations do not establish causality, a number of longitudinal studies suggest that experiencing physical punishment can have a direct causal impact on later aggressive behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Similar findings were reported in a 2010 study led by Catherine Taylor at Tulane University, which identified a link between maternal spanking of three-year-old children and an increased risk of later aggressive behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Straus contends that such evidence has often been overlooked, largely due to a prevailing belief that spanking is more effective than nonviolent forms of discipline.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] He warns, however, that this belief persists despite evidence of harmful side effects.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Cultural and political interpretations of aggression are further complicated by the subjective use of the term "aggressive", which may reflect value judgments depending on the observer's cultural or ideological standpoint.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Whether a coercive or violent act is viewed as aggression—or as legitimate or illegitimate aggression—often depends on the social positions of those involved relative to their culture's structure.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Cross-cultural research has found differences in attitudes towards aggression in different cultures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Within American culture, men from the southern United States were found in a study of university students to react more strongly and respond more aggressively than their northern counterparts when randomly insulted after being bumped into.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Other cultural frameworks frequently considered in aggression research include contrasts between individualistic and collectivist orientations.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] These may influence how individuals respond to disputes—for example, through open competition or by accommodating others and avoiding conflict.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] In a study including 62 countries, school principals reported higher levels of aggressive student behavior in cultures characterized as more individualistic and, correspondingly, less collectivist.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Other cross-cultural comparisons related to aggression and conflict have examined differences between democratic and authoritarian political systems, as well as between egalitarian and stratified societies.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The economic system known as capitalism has been interpreted by some scholars as relying on human competitiveness and aggression to drive the pursuit of resources and trade.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] This perspective has been viewed both positively, as a motivator for innovation and efficiency, and negatively, as a source of inequality and conflict.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Finally, the perceived legitimacy of aggressive acts are influenced by cultural and political attitudes regarding the social acceptability of certain actions or targets.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] These perceptions are often contested, particularly in cases involving religion or international disputes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] One prominent example is the Arab–Israeli conflict, where acts labeled as aggression by one group may be framed as defense or resistance by another.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Some researchers argue that behaviors such as aggression may be partially learned through observation and imitation of others, a concept rooted in social learning theory.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] This perspective includes the view that exposure to media violence may exert small effects on aggressive behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] However, this remains a subject of ongoing debate, and other scholars have challenged the strength or consistency of such effects.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] For example, a prospective study of adolescents found no long-term relationship between violent video game use and subsequent youth violence or bullying.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] A meta-analysis concluded that the effect of violent video games on aggression is generally smaller than that found in studies on television violence.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The magnitude of this effect was positively associated with the intensity of violent content and negatively associated with the amount of time spent playing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The study concluded that the available evidence was insufficient to establish a causal relationship between violent video games and increased aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Conversely, other research has reported associations between violent video game exposure and heightened aggressive thoughts, feelings, and behaviors both in laboratory settings and real-life contexts.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The frequency of physical aggression in humans peaks at around 2–3 years of age.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] These observations suggest that physical aggression is not only a learned behavior but that development provides opportunities for the learning and biological development of self-regulation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] However, a small subset of children fail to acquire all the necessary self-regulatory abilities and tend to show atypical levels of physical aggression across development.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] They may be at risk for later violent behavior or, conversely, a lack of aggression that may be considered necessary within society.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] However, some findings suggest that early aggression does not necessarily lead to aggression later on, although the course through early childhood is an important predictor of outcomes in middle childhood.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] In addition, physical aggression that continues is likely occurring in the context of family adversity, including socioeconomic factors.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Moreover, 'opposition' and 'status violations' in childhood appear to be more strongly linked to social problems in adulthood than simply aggressive antisocial behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Social learning through interactions in early childhood has been seen as a building block for levels of aggression which play a crucial role in the development of peer relationships in middle childhood.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Overall, an interplay of biological, social and environmental factors can be considered.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Some research indicates that changes in the weather can increase the likelihood of children exhibiting deviant behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The Bobo doll experiment was conducted by Albert Bandura in 1961.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] In this work, Bandura found that children exposed to an aggressive adult model acted more aggressively than those who were exposed to a nonaggressive adult model.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] This experiment suggests that anyone who comes in contact with and interacts with children can affect the way they react and handle situations.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Gender is a factor that plays a role in both human and animal aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Males are historically believed to be generally more physically aggressive than females from an early age, and men commit the vast majority of murders (Buss 2005).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] This is one of the most robust and reliable behavioral sex differences, and it has been found across many different age groups and cultures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] However, some empirical studies have found the discrepancy in male and female aggression to be more pronounced in childhood and the gender difference in adults to be modest when studied in an experimental context.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Still, there is evidence that males are quicker to aggression (Frey et al.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] 2003) and more likely than females to express their aggression physically.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] When considering indirect forms of non-violent aggression, such as relational aggression and social rejection, some scientists argue that females can be quite aggressive, although female aggression is rarely expressed physically.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] An exception is intimate partner violence that occurs among couples who are engaged, married, or in some other form of intimate relationship.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Although females are less likely than males to initiate physical violence, they can express aggression by using a variety of non-physical means.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Exactly which method women use to express aggression is something that varies from culture to culture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] On Bellona Island, a culture based on male dominance and physical violence, women tend to get into conflicts with other women more frequently than with men.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] When in conflict with males, instead of using physical means, they make up songs mocking the man, which spread across the island and humiliate him.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] If a woman wanted to kill a man, she would either convince her male relatives to kill him or hire an assassin.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Although these two methods involve physical violence, both are forms of indirect aggression, since the aggressor herself avoids getting directly involved or putting herself in immediate physical danger.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] See also the sections on testosterone and evolutionary explanations for gender differences above.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] There has been some links between those prone to violence and their alcohol use.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Those who are prone to violence and use alcohol are more likely to carry out violent acts.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Alcohol impairs judgment, making people much less cautious than they usually are (MacDonald et al.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] It also disrupts the way information is processed (Bushman 1993, 1997; Bushman & Cooper 1990).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Recent research further demonstrates that in everyday situations, violations of social norms can be perceived as provocations that trigger aggression, which can have negative consequences for individuals and social coexistence.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Based on the General Aggression Model (GAM), experimental evidence shows that physical provocation affects the internal state (cognition, arousal, and affect) of the provoked person and shapes their responses.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The social status of the provocateur can play a moderating role in this process: a higher-status provocateur induces a more aggression-prone internal state, but the likelihood of verbal retaliation is less affected by internal state when provocation comes from high status.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] These dynamics, illustrate how intentional provocation reduces the probability of ignoring the incident and increases the likelihood of verbal or physical aggression, mediated by changes in the internal state.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Overall, this mechanism highlights the importance of situational and social factors—such as status—in everyday aggression and its regulation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] This also adds to the currently inconclusive evidence about the role of the social status on aggression and highlights to importance of further inquiry.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Pain and discomfort also increase aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Even the simple act of placing one's hands in hot water can cause an aggressive response.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Hot temperatures have been implicated as a factor in a number of studies.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] One study completed in the midst of the civil rights movement found that riots were more likely on hotter days than cooler ones (Carlsmith & Anderson 1979).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Students were found to be more aggressive and irritable after taking a test in a hot classroom (Anderson et al.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Drivers in cars without air conditioning were also found to be more likely to honk their horns (Kenrick & MacFarlane 1986), which is used as a measure of aggression and has shown links to other factors such as generic symbols of aggression or the visibility of other drivers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Frustration is another major cause of aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The Frustration aggression theory states that aggression increases if a person feels that he or she is being blocked from achieving a goal (Aronson et al.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] One study found that the closeness to the goal makes a difference.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The study examined people waiting in line and concluded that the 2nd person was more aggressive than the 12th one when someone cut in line (Harris 1974).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Unexpected frustration may be another factor.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] In a separate study to demonstrate how unexpected frustration leads to increased aggression, Kulik & Brown (1979) selected a group of students as volunteers to make calls for charity donations.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] One group was told that the people they would call would be generous and the collection would be very successful.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The other group was given no expectations.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] The group that expected success was more upset when no one was pledging than the group who did not expect success (everyone actually had horrible success).
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] This research suggests that when an expectation does not materialize (successful collections), unexpected frustration arises which increases aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] There is some evidence to suggest that the presence of violent objects such as a gun can trigger aggression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] In a study done by Leonard Berkowitz and Anthony Le Page (1967), college students were made angry and then left in the presence of a gun or badminton racket.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] They were then led to believe they were delivering electric shocks to another student, as in the Milgram experiment.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Those who had been in the presence of the gun administered more shocks.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] It is possible that a violence-related stimulus increases the likelihood of aggressive cognitions by activating the semantic network.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] A new proposal links military experience to anger and aggression, developing aggressive reactions and investigating these effects on those possessing the traits of a serial killer.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] They come back to the civilian world and may still be haunted by flashbacks and nightmares, causing severe stress.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] In addition, it has been claimed that in the rare minority who are claimed to be inclined toward serial killing, violent impulses may be reinforced and refined in war, possibly creating more effective murderers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Some recent scholarship has questioned traditional psychological conceptualizations of aggression as universally negative.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Most traditional psychological definitions of aggression focus on the harm to the recipient of the aggression, implying this is the intent of the aggressor; however this may not always be the case.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] From this alternate view, although the recipient may or may not be harmed, the perceived intent is to increase the status of the aggressor, not necessarily to harm the recipient.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Such scholars contend that traditional definitions of aggression have no validity because of how challenging it is to study directly.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] From this view, rather than concepts such as assertiveness, aggression, violence and criminal violence existing as distinct constructs, they exist instead along a continuum with moderate levels of aggression being most adaptive.
[src:nonverbal-communication/aggression-p02] Such scholars do not consider this a trivial difference, noting that many traditional researchers' aggression measurements may measure outcomes lower down in the continuum, at levels which are adaptive, yet they generalize their findings to non-adaptive levels of aggression, thus losing precision.
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] The **Alaskan Athabascans**, **Alaskan Athapascans** or **Dena** (Russian: атабаски Аляски, атапаски Аляски) are Alaska Native peoples of the Athabaskan-speaking ethnolinguistic group.
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] They are considered the descendants of the original inhabitants of the interior of Alaska.
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] Formerly they identified as a people by the word **Tinneh** (nowadays **Dena**; cf.
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] Taken from their own language, it means simply "men" or "people".
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] In Alaska, where they are the oldest, there are eleven groups identified by the languages they speak.
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] The Alaskan Athabascan culture is an inland creek and river fishing (also coastal fishing by only Dena'ina of Cook Inlet) and hunter-gatherer culture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] The Alaskan Athabascans have a matrilineal system in which children belong to the mother's clan, with the exception of the Yupikized Athabaskans (Holikachuk and Deg Hit'an).
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] The Athabascan people hold potlatches which have religious, social and economic significance.
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] Dogs were their only domesticated animal, but were and are an integral element in their culture for the Athabascan population in North America.
[src:nonverbal-communication/alaskan-athabaskans] Athabascans are descended from Asian hunter-gatherers, likely originally native to Mongolia, who crossed the Bering Strait and settled in North America.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] Mehrabian, born in 1939 to an Armenian family in Iran, initially trained as an engineer, but gained renown for his research on the relative importance of verbal and nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] In addition to his scholarly work, Mehrabian developed several psychological assessment tools, including the Arousal Seeking Tendency Scale.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] His most famous contribution is the "7%-38%-55% Rule", also called "Mehrabian's Rule", which highlights the varying impact of words, tone of voice, and body language in conveying feelings and attitudes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] However, these findings have been misquoted and misinterpreted throughout human communication seminars worldwide.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] According to Mehrabian, when a person communicates feelings, the three elements of the message—words, tone of voice, and facial expression—contribute differently to how much others like the person.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] Specifically, words account for 7%, tone of voice for 38%, and facial expression for 55% of the liking.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] For effective communication about emotions, these three parts of the message need to align or be "congruent." If there is any incongruence, where the verbal and non-verbal cues contradict each other, the receiver might be confused or irritated by the conflicting messages.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] The following example should help illustrate incongruence in verbal and non-verbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] It becomes more likely that the receiver will trust the predominant form of communication, which to Mehrabian's findings is the non-verbal impact of tone+facial expression (38% + 55%), rather than the literal meaning of the words (7%).
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] It's important to note that Mehrabian's experiments focused specifically on communications of feelings and attitudes (like-dislike).
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] The disproportionate influence of tone of voice and facial expression becomes significant mainly in ambiguous situations, where the words spoken are inconsistent with the tone of voice or facial expression of the speaker.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] The "7%-38%-55%" rule has often been misinterpreted, leading to the claim that in any communication, the meaning of a message is conveyed mainly by non-verbal cues rather than by the meaning of words.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] However, this generalization stems from the specific conditions of Mehrabian's experiments and is a common mistake in applying his rule.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] For further details, references 286 and 305 in Silent Messages are cited as the original sources of Mehrabian's findings.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] The "7%-38%-55%" rule is based on two studies reported in the 1967 papers "Decoding of Inconsistent Communications", and "Inference of Attitudes from Nonverbal Communication in Two Channels".
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] Both studies focused on the communication of positive or negative emotions using single spoken words, such as "dear" or "terrible." The first study compared the relative importance of the semantic meaning of the word with the tone of voice and found that the latter was much more influential.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] The second study dealt with facial expressions (shown in black-and-white photographs) and vocal tone (as heard in a tape recording) and found that the relative contributions of the two communication channels had a ratio of 3:2.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] Mehrabian combined the results of these two studies to derive the ratio 7:38:55 for the relative importance of words, tone of voice, and facial expressions in conveying feelings and attitudes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] The study's applicability to real-life situations has several limitations that are often overlooked when the study is cited outside of a scientific context, contributing to potential misinterpretation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] First, the study is based on the interpretation of the meaning of a single tape of recorded words, which creates a very artificial context.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] Second, the figures are derived from combining results from two different studies, which may not be appropriate.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] Third, the study only relates to the communication of positive versus negative emotions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] Fourth, the study only included women, as men did not participate, which limits its generalizability.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] Fifth, other forms of nonverbal communication, such as body posture, were not considered in the studies.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] These limitations should be considered when interpreting the findings of the study.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] Subsequent studies have examined the relative impact of verbal and nonverbal signals in more natural settings.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] For example, a study in 1970 used video tapes to analyze the communication of submissive/dominant attitudes and found that all types of nonverbal cues, particularly body posture, had a 4.3 times greater impact than verbal cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] In contrast, a study in 1992 focused on the communication of happy/sad moods and discovered that hearing words spoken in a "flat" voice was approximately four times more influential than facial expressions seen in a silent film.
[src:nonverbal-communication/albert-mehrabian] These findings highlight the variability in conclusions that different studies may reach, depending on their methodologies.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In the same way that speech incorporates nonverbal components, collectively referred to as paralanguage and encompassing voice quality, rate, pitch, loudness, and speaking style, nonverbal communication also encompasses facets of one's voice.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Elements such as tone, inflection, emphasis, and other vocal characteristics contribute significantly to nonverbal communication, adding layers of meaning and nuance to the conveyed message.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Nonverbal communication involves the conscious and unconscious processes of encoding and decoding.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Encoding is defined as our ability to express emotions in a way that can be accurately interpreted by the receiver(s).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Decoding is called "nonverbal sensitivity", defined as the ability to take this encoded emotion and interpret its meanings accurately to what the sender intended.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Encoding is the act of generating information such as facial expressions, gestures, and postures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Encoding information utilizes signals which we may think to be universal.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Decoding is the interpretation of information from received sensations given by the encoder.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Culture plays an important role in nonverbal communication, and it is one aspect that helps to influence how we interact with each other.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In many Indigenous American communities, nonverbal cues and silence hold immense importance in deciphering the meaning of messages.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In such cultures, the context, relationship dynamics, and subtle nonverbal cues play a pivotal role in communication and interpretation, impacting how learning activities are organized and understood.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] This rule only applies in very specific situations, such as when someone is expressing feelings or attitudes, especially when words contradict tone and facial expression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] For most communication, like giving directions, teaching math, writing books etc.. verbal information carries most of the meaning.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Nonverbal communication can portray a message both vocally and with the correct body signals or gestures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Body signals consist of physical features, conscious and unconscious gestures and signals, and the mediation of personal space.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The wrong message can also be established if the body language conveyed does not match a verbal message.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Paying attention to both verbal and nonverbal communication may leave the listener with a feeling of being lost, due to not being able to breakdown both at the same time.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] However, ignoring nonverbal communication altogether would cause the listener to miss up to 60% of their communication, according to experts.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Nonverbal communication strengthens a first impression in common situations like attracting a partner or in a business interview: impressions are on average formed within the first four seconds of contact.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] First encounters or interactions with another person strongly affect a person's perception.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] When the other person or group is absorbing the message, they are focused on the entire environment around them, meaning the other person uses all five senses in the interaction: 83% sight, 11% hearing, 3% smell, 2% touch and 1% taste.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Many indigenous cultures use nonverbal communication in the integration of children at a young age into their cultural practices.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Children in these communities learn through observing and pitching in through which nonverbal communication is a key aspect of observation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Nonverbal communication encompasses a diverse range of signals that go beyond spoken language, such as gestures, facial expressions, body language, and vocal nuances like tone and rhythm.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] These cues carry subtle meanings critical to effective communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] For example, facial expressions are a powerful medium for conveying emotions, sometimes even through subtle microexpressions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] These microexpressions are fleeting, involuntary facial movements that briefly reveal genuine feeling.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] They often occur in a fraction of a second, offering a brief insight into a person's genuine emotions, some of which may not be intentionally expressed and may diverge from their consciously stated feelings.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] While some cues might be universally understood, others hold culture-specific significance, necessitating careful interpretation to prevent misunderstandings.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Understanding the tone, pitch, cultural connotations of touch, and environmental influences enriches nonverbal communication, shaping our interactions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Recognizing that cultural norms influence the appropriateness of tone and pitch is crucial, as outlined by display rules.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] This underscores the significance of being culturally sensitive when interpreting nonverbal cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In the context of intercultural communication, a deeper understanding of context culture becomes essential.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Context culture significantly shapes how individuals communicate emotions and convey meaning through nonverbal signals.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Being aware of these cultural nuances is fundamental for facilitating successful cross-cultural interactions and ensuring the accurate interpretation of nonverbal expressions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The understanding of tone, pitch, and cultural contexts in verbal communication complements nonverbal cues, offering a holistic grasp of interpersonal dynamics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The harmony or discrepancy between verbal and nonverbal signals significantly impacts message clarity.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In cultures where nonverbal cues are pivotal, incongruence between verbal and nonverbal elements can create confusion, while in cultures emphasizing explicit verbal communication, alignment between the two is essential for effective understanding.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Mastery of nonverbal signals extends beyond mere word comprehension, promoting cultural awareness and smoother interactions across diverse settings.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Proficiency in interpreting these cues not only aids in accurate understanding but also bolsters cross-cultural connections, enabling more profound exchanges.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Adeptness in nonverbal communication is crucial for navigating social situations, decoding nuanced human behaviors, and establishing meaningful connections in various contexts, underlining the interconnectedness and importance of both verbal and nonverbal forms of communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] An understanding of nonverbal communication’s role in information effects between the sender and receiver also contributes context for research of interpersonal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Understanding emotion thoroughly through observation of both parties’ emotional reactions from all senses is an important application to research by emphasizing interpersonal dynamics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Scientific research on nonverbal communication and behavior was started in 1872 with the publication of Charles Darwin's book, *The Expression of the Emotions in Man and Animals*.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In the book, Darwin argued that all mammals, both humans and animals, showed emotion through facial expressions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] For example, a species that attacked by biting, baring the teeth was a necessary act before an assault and wrinkling the nose reduced the inhalation of foul odors.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In response to the question asking why facial expressions persist even when they no longer serve their original purposes, Darwin's predecessors have developed a highly valued explanation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] According to Darwin, humans continue to make facial expressions because they have acquired communicative value throughout evolutionary history.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In other words, humans utilize facial expressions as external evidence of their internal state.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Although *The Expression of the Emotions in Man and Animals* was not one of Darwin's most successful books in terms of its quality and overall impact in the field, his initial ideas started the abundance of research on the types, effects, and expressions of nonverbal communication and behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Despite the introduction of nonverbal communication in the 1800s, the emergence of behaviorism in the 1920s paused further research on nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Behaviorism is defined as the theory of learning that describes people's behavior as acquired through conditioning.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Skinner trained pigeons to engage in various behaviors to demonstrate how animals engage in behaviors with rewards.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] While most psychology researchers were exploring behaviorism, the study of nonverbal communication as recorded on film began in 1955–56 at the Center for Advanced Study in Behavioral Sciences through a project which came to be called the *Natural History of an Interview*.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The initial participants included two psychiatrists, Frieda Fromm-Reichman and Henry Brosin, two linguists, Norman A.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] McQuown and Charles Hockett, and also two anthropologists, Clyde Kluckhohn and David M.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Schneider (these last two withdrew by the end of 1955, and did not participate in the major group project).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In their place, two other anthropologists, Ray Birdwhistell, already then known as the founder of kinesics, the study of body motion communication, and Gregory Bateson, known more generally as a human communication theorist, both joined the team in 1956.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Albert Scheflen and Adam Kendon were among those who joined one of the small research teams continuing research once the year at CASBS ended.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The project analyzed a film made by Bateson, using an analytic method called at the time *natural history*, and later, mostly by Scheflen, *context analysis*.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The result remained unpublished, as it was enormous and unwieldy, but it was available on microfilm by 1971.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The method involves transcribing filmed or videotaped behavior in excruciating detail, and was later used in studying the sequence and structure of human greetings, social behaviors at parties, and the function of posture during interpersonal interaction.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Research on nonverbal communication rocketed during the mid-1960s by a number of psychologists and researchers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Michael Argyle and Janet Dean Fodor, for example, studied the relationship between eye contact and conversational distance.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Exline examined patterns of looking while speaking and looking while listening.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Eckhard Hess produced several studies pertaining to pupil dilation that were published in *Scientific American*.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Robert Sommer studied the relationship between personal space and the environment.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Robert Rosenthal discovered that expectations made by teachers and researchers can influence their outcomes, and that subtle, nonverbal cues may play an important role in this process.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Albert Mehrabian studied the nonverbal cues of liking and immediacy.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] By the 1970s, a number of scholarly volumes in psychology summarized the growing body of research, such as Shirley Weitz's *Nonverbal Communication* and Marianne LaFrance and Clara Mayo's *Moving Bodies*.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Popular books included *Body Language* (Fast, 1970), which focused on how to use nonverbal communication to attract other people, and *How to Read a Person Like a Book* (Nierenberg & Calero, 1971) which examined nonverbal behavior in negotiation situations.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The journal *Environmental Psychology and Nonverbal Behavior* was founded in 1976.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In 1970, Argyle hypothesized that although spoken language is used for communicating the meaning about events external to the person communicating, the nonverbal codes are used to create and strengthen interpersonal relationships.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] When someone wishes to avoid conflicting or embarrassing events during communication, it is considered proper and correct by the hypothesis to communicate attitudes towards others non-verbally instead of verbally.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Beliefs surrounding nonverbal communication continue to evolve, and these behaviors go deeper than just body language and facial expressions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Misconceptions made by knowledgeable psychologists and laypersons alike show 3 main topics regularly mistaken.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Research challenges the assumption that personal space is fixed, suggesting that it varies based on cultural context, relationships, and situational factors.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Another point recognized to be false is that facial expressions universally reveal inner emotions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] On the contrary, facial expressions may be shaped by an individual's culture or social gaps, meaning they may not be a gateway to specific emotions often associated with obvious signs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] A third misconception elaborates on the idea that the body never lies, and nonverbal cues effectively reveal deception.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Debunked by other professionals, these behaviors do not always provide hidden insight into a person's truthfulness.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] It takes just one-tenth of a second for someone to judge and make their first impression.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] According to a study from Princeton University, this short amount of time is enough for a person to determine several attributes about an individual.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] These attributes included "attractiveness, likeability, trustworthiness, competence, and aggressiveness." A first impression is a lasting non-verbal communicator.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The way a person portrays themselves on the first encounter is non-verbal statement to the observer.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Presentation can include clothing and other visible attributes such as facial expressions or facial traits in general.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Negative impressions can also be based on presentation and on personal prejudice.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] First impressions, although sometimes misleading, can in many situations be an accurate depiction of others.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In terms of culture, collectivists have a harder time changing their first impressions because they emphasize a lot more context and need additional time when faced with new clues as each view may be correct in some contexts.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Moreover, Fang et al., acknowledged that first impression is less likely to change in Asian culture because they value cohesiveness and consensus, thus will not destroy their group cohesiveness at the expense of changing their first impression when they reached a consensus.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Posture is a nonverbal cue that is associated with positioning.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Posture and positioning are sources of information about individual's characteristics, attitudes, and feelings about themselves and other people.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] There are many different types of body positioning to portray certain postures, including slouching, towering, legs spread, jaw thrust, shoulders forward, and arm crossing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The posture or bodily stance an individual exhibits communicates a variety of messages.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] A study, for instance, identified around 200 postures that are related to maladjustment and withholding of information.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Posture can be used to determine a participant's degree of attention or involvement, the difference in status between communicators, and the level of fondness a person has for the other communicator, depending on body "openness".
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] It can also be effectively used as a way for an individual to convey a desire to increase, limit, or avoid interaction with another person.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] People will change their posture relative to the situation they are in.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] This can be demonstrated in the case of relaxed posture when an individual is within a nonthreatening situation and the way one's body tightens or become rigid when under stress.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Clothing is one of the most common forms of non-verbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The study of clothing and other objects as a means of non-verbal communication is known as *artifactics* or *objectics*.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The types of clothing that an individual wears convey nonverbal cues about their personality, background and financial status, and how others will respond to them.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] An individual's clothing style can demonstrate their culture, mood, level of confidence, interests, age, authority, and values/beliefs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] For instance, Jewish men may wear a yarmulke to outwardly communicate their religious belief.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Similarly, clothing can communicate what nationality a person or group is; for example, in traditional festivities Scottish men often wear kilts to specify their culture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Aside from communicating a person's beliefs and nationality, clothing can be used as a nonverbal cue to attract others.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Men and women may shower themselves with accessories and high-end fashion to attract partners interested.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In this case, clothing is a form of self-expression where people can flaunt their power, wealth, sex appeal, or creativity.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] A study of the clothing worn by women attending discothèques, carried out in Vienna, Austria.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] It showed that in certain groups of women (especially women who were without their partners), motivation for sex and levels of sexual hormones were correlated with aspects of their clothing, especially the amount of skin displayed and the presence of sheer clothing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The way one chooses to dress tells a lot about one's personality.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The University of North Carolina studied how undergraduate women chose to dress and their personality types.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The study showed that women dressed "primarily for comfort and practicality were more self-controlled, dependable, and socially well adjusted." Women who did not like to stand out in a crowd typically had more conservative and traditional views and beliefs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Clothing, although non-verbal, tells people what the individual's personality is.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The way a person dresses is typically rooted in deeper internal motivations such as emotions, experiences, and culture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Clothing expresses who they are or who they want to be that day.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] It shows other people who they want to be associated with and where they fit in.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Clothing can start relationships because they clue other people into the wearer.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] When it comes to the clothing that they wear, nonverbal communication with gangs is very common.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Gang members typically wear 2–3 colors to signify that they are representing a particular neighborhood.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Baseball caps and hats with specific gang names and initials, worn backwards, tilted, in certain colors, etc. bandanas worn around the head, shoulders, arms, or legs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Gang members frequently dress in hip-hop-inspired fashions, such as oversized pants worn below the waist (also known as "sagging").
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Colored belts, colored shoes, and colored bandanas are all utilized as identifiers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Group colors and clothing are commonly used to represent affiliation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Gestures may be made with the hands, arms or body, and also include movements of the head, face and eyes, such as winking, nodding, or rolling one's eyes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Although the study of gesture is still in its infancy, some broad categories of gestures have been identified by researchers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The most familiar are the so-called emblems or quotable gestures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] These are conventional, culture-specific gestures that can be used as replacement for words, such as the hand wave used in western cultures for "hello" and "goodbye".
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] A single emblematic gesture can have a very different significance in different cultural contexts, ranging from complimentary to highly offensive.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] For a list of emblematic gestures, see List of gestures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] There are some universal gestures like the shoulder shrug.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Gestures can also be categorized as either speech independent or speech related.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Speech-independent gestures are dependent upon culturally accepted interpretation and have a direct verbal translation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] A wave or a peace sign are examples of speech-independent gestures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Speech-related gestures are used in parallel with verbal speech; this form of nonverbal communication is used to emphasize the message that is being communicated.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Speech-related gestures are intended to provide supplemental information to a verbal message such as pointing to an object of discussion.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Gestures are not just for the audience but can also help the speaker elaborate their thoughts, and process their ideas more fluently.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] As an example: giving directions for a place and pointing directionally to remind oneself of the correct route.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] This is not only to help the listener, but also to help the speaker visualize the route as though they were moving through it.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Facial expressions, more than anything, serve as a practical means of communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] With all the various muscles that precisely control mouth, lips, eyes, nose, forehead, and jaw, human faces are estimated to be capable of more than ten thousand different expressions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] This versatility makes non-verbals of the face extremely efficient and honest, unless deliberately manipulated.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In addition, many of these emotions, including happiness, sadness, anger, fear, surprise, disgust, shame, anguish and interest are universally recognized.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Displays of emotions can generally be categorized into two groups: negative and positive.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Negative emotions usually manifest as increased tension in various muscle groups: tightening of jaw muscles, furrowing of forehead, squinting eyes, or lip occlusion (when the lips seemingly disappear).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In contrast, positive emotions are revealed by the loosening of the furrowed lines on the forehead, relaxation of the muscles around the mouth, and widening of the eye area.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] When individuals are truly relaxed and at ease, the head will also tilt to the side, exposing our most vulnerable area, the neck.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] This is a high-comfort display, often seen during courtship, that is nearly impossible to mimic when tense or suspicious.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Some hand movements are not considered to be gestures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] They consist of manipulations either of the person or some object (e.g. clothing, pencils, eyeglasses)—the kinds of scratching, fidgeting, rubbing, tapping, and touching that people often do with their hands.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] These behaviors can show that a person is experiencing anxiety or feeling of discomfort, typical when the individual is not the one in control of the conversation or situation and therefore expresses this uneasiness subconsciously.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Such behaviors are referred to as adapters.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] They are movements with specific, conventionalized meanings called symbolic gestures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] They are the exact opposite of adaptors, since their meanings are intended to be communicated and they have a specific meaning for the person who gives the gesture and the person to receive it.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Familiar symbolic gestures include the "raised fist," "bye-bye," and "thumbs up." In contrast to adapters, symbolic gestures are used intentionally and serve a clear communicative function.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Sign languages are highly developed systems of symbolic gesture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Some educators that work with deaf learners use a combination of cued speech and lip speaking and reading that helps deaf and hard hearing individuals (D/HH) to code and decode words based on their phonetics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In addition to the supplementary aspect of the cues like location and movement, every culture has their own set of gestures, some of which are unique only to a specific culture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] For example, the phonological and lexical repository of D/HH individuals is highly dependent on their social background and richness of language.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Very similar gestures can have very different meanings across cultures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Symbolic gestures are usually used in the absence of speech but can also accompany speech.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The middle ground between adapters and symbolic gestures is occupied by conversational gestures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] These gestures do not refer to actions or words but do accompany speech.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Conversational gestures are hand movements that accompany speech and are related to the speech they accompany.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Though they do accompany speech, conversational gestures are not seen in the absence of speech and are only made by the person who is speaking.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] There are a few types of conversational gestures, specifically motor and lexical movements.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Motor movements are those which are rhythmical and repetitive, do not have to be accompanied by anything spoken due to their simple meaning, and the speaker's hand usually sticks to one position.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] When paired with verbal communication, they can be used to stress certain syllables.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] An example of this would be pointing someone in the direction of an individual and saying, "That way." In this case, the "That" in the sentence would be stressed by the movements.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Lexical movements are more complex, not rhythmic, or repetitive, but rather lengthy and varied.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] An example of this would be something like giving elaborate directions to somewhere and pairing that with various hands movements to signal the various turns to take.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Hall, the amount of space we maintain between ourselves and the persons with whom we are communicating shows the importance of the science of proxemics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In this process, it is seen how we feel towards the others at that particular time.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Intimate distance is considered appropriate for familiar relationships and indicates closeness and trust.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Personal distance is still close but keeps another "at arm's length" and is considered the most comfortable distance for most of our interpersonal contact, while social distance is used for the kind of communication that occurs in business relationships and, sometimes, in the classroom.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Public distance occurs in situations where two-way communication is not desirable or possible.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Proxemics plays a crucial role in getting to know someone.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Imagine two individuals sitting at a small dinner table.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] One person, motivated by romantic interest, begins to lean in, lightly touching the other's arm and shifting their chair closer.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] They are operating within the intimate zone, expecting closeness.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] However, the other person, who does not share the same romantic feelings, perceives this behavior as a breach of social norms.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] They expected the interaction to remain within personal distance, a more appropriate zone for acquaintances or casual dates.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] As a result, they may respond by pulling away, crossing their arms, or showing visible discomfort signals of a desire to re-establish that personal boundary.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In addition, to social expectations, cultural can play a role in proxemics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] People from different cultures have different comfort zones when it comes to personal space (Chen & Starosta, 2005).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In everyday conversations, people from places like North Africa, and parts of the Middle East usually feel fine standing closer to others.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] On the other hand, people from Japan and China often prefer more space between themselves and others.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Not understanding these differences can make cross-cultural interactions feel awkward or uncomfortable.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] For example, someone from a culture that's used to standing close might keep moving forward if the other person keep stepping back.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Meanwhile, someone who's used to more space might feel uneasy or confused if someone stands too close.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Eye contact is the instance when two people look at each other's eyes at the same time; it is the primary nonverbal way of indicating engagement, interest, attention and involvement.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Nonverbal communication involves the conscious and unconscious processes of *encoding* and *decoding*.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Encoding is defined as our ability to express emotions in a way that the receiver(s).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Decoding is called "*nonverbal sensitivity*", defined as the ability to take this encoded emotion and interpret its meanings accurately to what the sender intended.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Some studies have demonstrated that people use their eyes to indicate interest.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] This includes frequently recognized actions of winking and movements of the eyebrows.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Disinterest is highly noticeable when little or no eye contact is made in a social setting.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] When an individual is interested, however, the pupils will dilate.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] According to Eckman, "Eye contact (also called mutual gaze) is another major channel of nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The duration of eye contact is its most meaningful aspect." Generally speaking, the longer there is established eye contact between two people, the greater the intimacy levels.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Gaze comprises the actions of looking while talking and listening.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The length of a gaze, the frequency of glances, patterns of fixation, pupil dilation, and blink rate are all important cues in nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] According to Descroix et al., the context of conversations does not produce long blinks between the emitter and the recipient.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Along with the detection of disinterest, deceit can also be observed in a person.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Hogan states "when someone is being deceptive their eyes tend to blink a lot more.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Eyes act as leading indicator of truth or deception," Both nonverbal and verbal cues are useful when detecting deception.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] It is typical for people who are detecting lies to rely consistently on verbal cues but this can hinder how well they detect deception.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Those who are lying and those who are telling the truth possess different forms of nonverbal and verbal cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Understanding the cultural background of a person will influence how easily deception is detectable because nonverbal cues may differ depending on the culture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In addition to eye contact these nonverbal cues can consist of physiological aspects including pulse rate as well as levels of perspiration.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In addition eye aversion can be predictive of deception.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Eye aversion is the avoidance of eye contact.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Eye contact and facial expressions provide important social and emotional information.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Overall, as Pease states, "Give the amount of eye contact that makes everyone feel comfortable.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In concealing deception, nonverbal communication makes it easier to lie without being revealed.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] This is the conclusion of a study where people watched made-up interviews of persons accused of having stolen a wallet.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The interviewees lied in about 50% of the cases.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] People had access to either written transcript of the interviews, or audio tape recordings, or video recordings.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] The more clues that were available to those watching, the larger was the trend that interviewees who actually lied were judged to be truthful.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] That is, people that are clever at lying can use tone of voice and facial expressions to give the impression that they are truthful.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Contrary to popular belief, a liar does not always avoid eye contact.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In an attempt to be more convincing, liars deliberately made more eye contact with interviewers than those that were telling the truth.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] However, there are many cited examples of cues to deceit, delivered via nonverbal (paraverbal and visual) communication channels, through which deceivers supposedly unwittingly provide clues to their concealed knowledge or actual opinions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Most studies examining the nonverbal cues to deceit rely upon human coding of video footage (c.f.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Vrij, 2008), although a recent study also demonstrated bodily movement differences between truth-tellers and liars using an automated body motion capture system.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Olfactic communication is a channel of nonverbal communication referring to the various ways people and animals communicate and engage in social interaction through their sense of smell.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Our human olfactory sense is one of the most phylogenetically primitive and emotionally intimate of the five senses; the sensation of smell is thought to be the most matured and developed human sense.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Human ancestors essentially depended on their sense of smell to alert themselves of danger such as poisonous food and to locate potent mating partners.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Using the sense of smell as an instrument paved a way for smell to become a platform of nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Smell also has a significant influence on social interactions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Through their branch of olfaction research, the National Science Foundation recorded that over 70 percent of American adults believe a person's body odor has a significant effect on how interested they will be when conversing with people of a different sex.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] This process is possible with olfactory bulbs, the part of the brain that discriminates and enhances certain odors.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Typically, women will prefer men whose natural odor is similar to their own, while heterosexual men are attracted to females with high estrogen levels and strong menstrual secretions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] An entire industry has been developed to provide people with personal smell-masking products, such as perfume, cologne, deodorant, and scented lotions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] When a person covers their natural body odor with a pleasant smell, they are communicating their desire to be attractive either emotionally, sexually, or romantically.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Nonverbal communication stands in contrast to communication through words, but includes other aspects of the speech signal.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] In particular, prosody, and in particular vocalics, plays a very important part in nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Prosodic properties such as tempo, volume, inflection, pauses, and pitch can combine to communicate emotion and attitude without using specific words.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Vocalics also includes emblems, or sounds with specific meanings, such as vocalizing "brrr" when cold, and mental-state indicators, like "hmm" when thinking about something, and other nonlexical but meaningful sounds.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] These sounds are often accompanied by other nonverbal cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Infants heavily rely on nonverbal vocalics to communicate their needs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] As caregivers talk with their baby, the baby can pick up intonation as well start to mimic and use it themselves.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] As they go on, babies can pick up more and learn how to develop their own voices and vocalics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Furthermore, in a study highlighted by Pearce and Conklin, they found that changing the vocalics of an audio recording of the same speech gave different results of liking.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] When the speaker gave his speech as more conversational instead of dynamic, he was deemed more trust worthy.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Vocalics can heavily influence communication through its many different cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Online nonverbal communication is nonverbal communication done through an online medium, such as text messaging and video calling.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Whilst it may differ from face-to-face communication and cues, it retains similar importance when it comes to relaying information between individuals.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Elements such as Emojis and GIFs provide crucial information of context or emotion to aid in understanding despite the physical barrier when text messaging.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Within video, cues like gestures, facial expressions, and body language are observed to be displayed stronger than usual to properly articulate emotion and meaning.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p01] Nonverbal cues being used through online mediums have been observed enhancing social presence, or the showcasing of personal characteristics within an online community, by giving personal or emotional information and contributing to engagement in online environments.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] While not traditionally thought of as "talk," nonverbal communication has been found to contain highly precise and symbolic meanings, similar to verbal speech.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] However the meanings in nonverbal communication are conveyed through the use of gesture, posture changes, and timing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nuances across different aspects of nonverbal communication can be found in cultures all around the world.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] These differences can often lead to miscommunication between people of different cultures, who usually do not mean to offend.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Differences can be based in preferences for mode of communication, like the Chinese, who prefer silence over verbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Differences can even be based on how cultures perceive the passage of time.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Chronemics, how people handle time, can be categorized in two ways: polychronic which is when people do many activities at once and is common in Italy and Spain, or monochronic which is when people do one thing at a time which is common in America.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Because nonverbal communication can vary across many axes—gestures, gaze, clothing, posture, direction, or even environmental cues like lighting—there is a lot of room for cultural differences.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In Japan, a country which prides itself on the best customer service, workers tend to use wide arm gestures to give clear directions to strangers—accompanied by the ever-present bow to indicate respect.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] One of the main factors that differentiates nonverbal communication in cultures is high and low-context.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Context relates to certain events and the meaning that is ultimately derived from it.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] "High-context" cultures rely mostly on nonverbal cues and gestures, using elements such as the closeness of the kind of the relationships they have with others, strict social hierarchies and classes and deep cultural tradition and widely known beliefs and rules.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In contrast, "low-context" cultures depend largely on words and verbal communication, where communications are direct and social hierarchies are way less tense and more loose.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Gestures vary widely across cultures in how they are used and what they mean.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In the United States, pointing is the gesture of a finger or hand to indicate or "come here please" when beckoning a dog.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] But pointing with one finger is also considered to be rude by some cultures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Those from Asian cultures typically use their entire hand to point to something.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Other examples include, sticking one's tongue out.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In Western countries, it can be seen as mockery, but in Polynesia it serves as a greeting and a sign of reverence.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Clapping is a North American way of applauding, but in Spain is used to summon a waiter at a restaurant.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Differences in nodding and shaking the head to indicate agreement and disagreement also exist.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Northern Europeans nodding their heads up and down to say "yes", and shaking their head from side to side to say "no".
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] But the Greeks have for at least three thousand years used the upward nod for disagreement and the downward nod for agreement.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] There are many ways of waving goodbye: Americans face the palm outward and move the hand side to side, Italians face the palm inward and move the fingers facing the other person, French and Germans face the hand horizontal and move the fingers toward the person leaving.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Gestures are used in more informal settings and more often by children.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] People in the United States commonly use the "OK" hand gesture to give permission and allow an action.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In Japan, however, the same sign means "money".
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] It refers to "zero" or "nothing" in several cultures besides these two (Argentina, Belgium, French and the Portuguese).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] To Eastern European cultures that same "OK" sign is considered a vulgar swearing gesture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In certain Commonwealth cultures, the index and middle fingers only extended with the palm pointing outwards can be an insulting gesture, while in others it simply means the number "two" or the "V for Victory" sign, while the same sign with the palm pointing inwards means "peace" in some cultures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Speech-independent gestures are nonverbal cues that communicate a word or an expression, most commonly a dictionary definition.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Though differences in this area exist between cultures, speech-independent gestures must have a common understanding among people affiliated with that culture or subculture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] As most people use gestures to better clarify their speech, speech-independent gestures do not rely on speech for their meaning.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Usually they transpire into a single gesture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] There are several such gestures that could be performed through the face.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For example, a nose wrinkle could universally mean disapproval or disgust.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Depending on the culture, a nod or head bobble can indicate understanding while the speaker is talking.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Even though speech-independent gestures are independent of speech, it may still require context to fully interpret.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Gestures with the middle finger may be used within different contexts, comical or derogatory: the only way to know is if one analyzes the other behaviors surrounding it and depending on who the speaker is and who the speaker is addressing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Emotions are a key factor in nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Just as gestures and other hand movements vary across cultures, so does the way people display their emotions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For example, "In many cultures, such as the Arab and Iranian cultures, people express grief openly.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] They mourn out loud, while in Asian cultures, the general belief is that it is unacceptable to show emotion openly." For people in Westernized countries, laughter is a sign of amusement, but in some parts of Africa it is a sign of wonder or embarrassment.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Emotional expression varies with culture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Native Americans tend to be more reserved and less expressive with emotions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The Yoruba (Nigeria) have taught their children to follow certain nonverbal commands, such as winking, which tells them it is time to leave the room.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] To the Chinese it comes off as an offensive gesture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Emotional expression as touch between different levels of relationships can vary upon culture as well.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Within Japanese culture, touch is something that is uncommon when speaking to another person, particularly friends or acquaintances.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] By contrast, within South American and South European cultures, frequent contact between people, even if they have just met, is commonplace and showcases a differing emphasis on physical contact as hospitality.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In the United States, there are varying degrees of people’s perception of appropriate physical contact.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Some will not want physical contact at all, even from acquaintances, but others may only want physical contact with those who they are close to, like greeting a longtime friend with a hug.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Hall’s foundational models of cultures that are high- and low-contact when it comes to emotional expression through proxemics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This cultural difference in how emotions are expressed through nonverbal communication comes from perceptions and expectations, particularly in public.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For example, within the Japanese culture, crowding is common and people who are close show it through physical proximity.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] By contrast, in Middle Eastern culture, space between individuals, is held more sacred and commonplace.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] According to Matsumoto and Juang, the nonverbal motions of different people indicate important channels of communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal actions should match and harmonize with the message being portrayed, otherwise confusion will occur.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For instance, an individual would normally not be seen smiling and gesturing broadly when saying a sad message.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The author states that nonverbal communication is very important to be aware of, especially if comparing gestures, gaze, and tone of voice amongst different cultures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] As Latin American cultures embrace big speech gestures, Middle Eastern cultures are relatively more modest in public and are not expressive.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Within cultures, different rules are made about staring or gazing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Women may especially avoid eye contact with men because it can be taken as a sign of sexual interest.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In some cultures, gaze can be seen as a sign of respect.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In Western culture, eye contact is interpreted as attentiveness and honesty.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In Hispanic, Asian, Middle Eastern, and Native American cultures, eye contact is thought to be disrespectful or rude, and lack of eye contact does not mean that a person is not paying attention.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Voice is a category that changes within cultures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Depending on whether or not the cultures is expressive or non-expressive, many variants of the voice can depict different reactions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The acceptable physical distance is another major difference in the nonverbal communication between cultures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In Latin America and the Middle East the acceptable distance is much shorter than what most Europeans and Americans feel comfortable with.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This is why an American or a European might wonder why the other person is invading their personal space by standing so close, while the other person might wonder why the American/European is standing so far from them.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In the opposite way, most Native Americans value distance to protect themselves.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal communication is commonly used to facilitate learning in indigenous American communities.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal communication is pivotal for collaborative participation in shared activities, as children from indigenous American communities will learn how to interact using nonverbal communication by intently observing adults.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal communication allows for continuous keen observation and signals to the learner when participation is needed.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Culture plays an important role in nonverbal communication, and it is one aspect that helps to influence how learning activities are organized.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In many Indigenous American Communities, for example, there is often an emphasis on nonverbal communication, which acts as a valued means by which children learn.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] A key characteristic of this type of nonverbal learning is that children have the opportunity to observe and interact with all parts of an activity.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Many Indigenous American children are in close contact with adults and other children who are performing the activities that they will eventually master.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Objects and materials become familiar to the child as the activities are a normal part of everyday life.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Learning is done in an extremely contextualized environment rather than one specifically tailored to be instructional.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For example, the direct involvement that Mazahua children take in the marketplace is used as a type of interactional organization for learning without explicit verbal instruction.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Children learn how to run a market stall, take part in caregiving, and also learn other basic responsibilities through non-structured activities, cooperating voluntarily within a motivational context to participate.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Not explicitly instructing or guiding the children teaches them how to integrate into small coordinated groups to solve a problem through consensus and shared space.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] These Mazahua separate-but-together practices have shown that participation in everyday interaction and later learning activities establishes enculturation that is rooted in nonverbal social experience.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] As the children participate in everyday interactions, they are simultaneously learning the cultural meanings behind these interactions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Children's experience with nonverbally organized social interaction helps constitute the process of enculturation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In some Indigenous communities of the Americas, children reported one of their main reasons for working in their home was to build unity within the family, the same way they desire to build solidarity within their own communities.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Most indigenous children learn the importance of putting in this work in the form of nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Evidence of this can be observed in a case study where children are guided through the task of folding a paper figure by observing the posture and gaze of those who guide them through it.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This is projected onto homes and communities, as children wait for certain cues from others to initiative cooperate and collaborate.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] When children are closely related to the context of the endeavor as active participants, coordination is based on a shared reference, which helps to allow, maintain, and promote nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The idea of "context-embeddedness" allows nonverbal communication to be a means of learning within Native American Alaskan Athabaskans and Cherokee communities.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] By observing various family and community social interactions, social engagement is dominated through nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For example, when children elicit thoughts or words verbally to their elders, they are expected to structure their speech carefully.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This demonstrates cultural humility and respect as excessive acts of speech when conversational genre shifts reveal weakness and disrespect.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This careful self-censorship exemplifies traditional social interaction of Athapaskin and Cherokee Native Americans who are mostly dependent on nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal cues are used by most children in the Warm Springs Indian Reservation community within the parameters of their academic learning environments.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This includes referencing Native American religion through stylized hand gestures in colloquial communication, verbal and nonverbal emotional self-containment, and less movement of the lower face to structure attention on the eyes during face-to-face engagement.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Therefore, children's approach to social situations within a reservation classroom, for example, may act as a barrier to a predominantly verbal learning environment.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Most Warm Springs children benefit from a learning model that suits a nonverbal communicative structure of collaboration, traditional gesture, observational learning and shared references.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] While nonverbal communication is more prevalent in Indigenous American Communities, verbal communication is also used.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Preferably, verbal communication does not substitute one's involvement in an activity, but instead acts as additional guidance or support towards the completion of an activity.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] As much of human communication is nonverbal, learning a language without learning its corresponding pragmatics can lead to miscommunication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] "This can lead to intercultural conflict (according to Marianna Pogosyan Ph.D.), misunderstandings and ambiguities in communication, despite language fluency." Nonverbal communication makes the difference between bringing cultures together in understanding one another, appearing authentic.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Or it can push people farther away due to misunderstandings in how different groups see certain nonverbal cues or gestures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] From birth, children in various cultures are taught the gestures and cues their culture defines as universal which is not the case for others, but some movements are universal.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Evidence suggests that smiling when happy, and frowning in response to something upsetting or bad, are culturally universal.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Some cues are culturally learned and become habitual, others are hereditary.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] These nature versus nurture questions are still debated.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Along with gestures, physical traits can also convey certain messages in nonverbal communication, for instance, eye color, hair color and height.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Research into height has generally found that taller people are perceived as being more impressive.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Melamed and Bozionelos (1992) studied a sample of managers in the United Kingdom and found that height was a key factor in who was promoted.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Our use of time can communicate and send messages, nonverbally.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The way we use time and give or do not give our time to others can communicate different messages.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Chronemics can send messages to others about what we value and also send messages about power.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] "When you go to see someone who is in a position of power over you, such as your supervisor, it is not uncommon to be kept waiting.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] However, you would probably consider it bad form to make a more powerful person wait for you.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal communication plays a crucial role in effectively transmitting messages.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Beginning from birth and persisting throughout one's life, it undergoes a developmental progression encompassing three phases, ranging from initial dyadic exchanges to the integration of both verbal and nonverbal cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] With diverse functions, nonverbal communication acts as a substitute for verbal interaction in situations where verbalization is unnecessary or impossible.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] It adds clarity to communication by unveiling emotional states and articulating specific feelings.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This is achieved through various nonverbal elements such as emblems, illustrators, regulators, adaptors, and vocalics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This system is shaped by component including paralinguistics, kinesics, tactile communication, and proxemics, influencing social, academic, and professional contexts.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Despite frequently being overlooked, nonverbal cues possess the potential to convey up to 80% of a message, especially holding significance in interactions involving prelinguistic infants and individuals who have severe disabilities.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The cultural nuances of these cues underscore the necessity for interpretation, emphasizing the contextual, signaling, and interpretative dimensions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Kinesics is defined as movements, more specifically the study of our movements involving our hands, body, and face.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The term was coined by Ray Birdwhistell, who considered the term body language inaccurate and instead opted to explain it as nonverbal behaviors stemming from body movement.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Research around this behavior provides some examples, such as someone casually smiling and leaning forward, as well as maintaining eye contact to radiate a non-dominating and intimate demeanor.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In contrast, someone leaning back, a stoic facial expression, and no to little eye contact could emit an unfriendly and dominating demeanor.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Additional research expresses that eye contact is an important part of nonverbal communication involved in kinesics, as longer and appropriate levels of eye contact give an individual credibility.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The opposite is said for those who do not maintain eye contact, as they are likely to be deemed distrustful.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] More eye contact was also found to be related to higher levels of likability and believability from those people interacted with.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] A real-life example of this is through service workers, in a study it was found that those workers who welcomed customers with smiles seemed like warmer individuals than those who did not smile.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Customers reported that those without smiles and open body movements, such as waving or handshaking, were lacking warmth and deemed less friendly.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Haptics is the study of touching as nonverbal communication, and haptic communication refers to how people and other animals communicate via touching.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Touches among humans that can be defined as communication include handshakes, holding hands, kissing (cheek, lips, hand), back slapping, high fives, a pat on the shoulder, and brushing an arm.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Touching of oneself may include licking, picking, holding, and scratching.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] These behaviors are referred to as "adapters" or "tells" and may send messages that reveal the intentions or feelings of a communicator and a listener.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The meaning conveyed from touch is highly dependent upon the culture, the context of the situation, the relationship between communicators, and the manner of touch.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Touch is an extremely important sense for humans; as well as providing information about surfaces and textures it is a component of nonverbal communication in interpersonal relationships, and vital in conveying physical intimacy.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] It can be both sexual (such as kissing) and platonic (such as hugging or tickling).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Touch is the earliest sense to develop in the fetus.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Human babies have been observed to have enormous difficulty surviving if they do not possess a sense of touch, even if they retain sight and hearing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Babies who can perceive through touch, even without sight and hearing, tend to fare much better.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In chimpanzees, the sense of touch is highly developed.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] As newborns, they see and hear poorly but cling strongly to their mothers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Touching is treated differently from one country to another and socially acceptable levels of touching vary from one culture to another (Remland, 2009).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In Thai culture, for example, touching someone's head may be thought rude.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Remland and Jones (1995) studied groups of people communicating and found that touching was rare among the English (8%), the French (5%) and the Dutch (4%) compared to Italians (14%) and Greeks (12.5%).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Striking, pushing, pulling, pinching, kicking, strangling and hand-to-hand fighting are forms of touch in the context of physical abuse.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In the *Journal of Nonverbal Behavior,* McDaniel et al. assessed touch as a form of communication among people from different nations under the lens of culture, relationships, and a number of body areas touched.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Latin Americans are known to have a high degree of tactile activity in contrast to Asians who are considered a no-contact culture as they often steer away from public display of affection (PDA).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Proxemics is the use of space as a form of communication, and includes how far or near participants position themselves from each other.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] It can be influenced by culture, race/ethnicity, gender, and age.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Hall invented the term when he realized that culture influences how people use space in communication while working with diplomats, and published his findings on proxemics in 1959 as *The Silent Language*.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Proxemics also play a big role in business as research shows that gender and invasion of customers' privacy without previous ties negatively affect the outcome of deals.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Besides, in high contact cultures, people are generally more comfortable in closer proximity, whereas individuals in low contact cultures feel more comfortable with a greater amount of personal space.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Hall concluded that proxemics could cause misunderstandings between cultures as cultures use of proxemics varies and what is customary in one culture may range from being confusing to being offensive to members of a different culture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] According to Hall, the amount of space we maintain between ourselves and the persons we communicate with shows the importance of the science of proxemics.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In this process, it is seen how we feel towards others at that particular time.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This resonates with proxemics and viewing it through the cultural lens, people use their space differently because of the meaning behind it as in a spectrum of cultures, ideologies differ.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Within American culture, Hall defines four primary distance zones: (i) intimate (touching to eighteen inches) distance, (ii) personal (eighteen inches to four feet) distance, (iii) social (four to twelve feet) distance, and (iv) public (more than twelve feet) distance.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Intimate space is any distance less than 18 inches, and is most commonly used by individuals when they are engaging with someone with whom they feel very comfortable, such as a spouse, partner, friend, child, or parent.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Personal space is a distance of 18 inches to 4 feet and is usually used when individuals are interacting with friends.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Social distance is the most common type of proximity as it is used when communicating with colleagues, classmates, acquaintances, or strangers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Public distance creates the greatest gap between the individual and the audience and is categorized as distances greater than 12 feet in distance and is often used for speeches, lectures, or formal occasions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Differentiating which parts of a face-to-face conversation are communicated verbally versus non-verbally is not straightforward.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Other studies done on the same subject have concluded that in more relaxed and natural settings of communication, verbal and non-verbal signals and cues can contribute in surprisingly similar ways.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The most important effect was that body posture communicated superior status (specific to culture and context said person grew up in) in a very efficient way.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] On the other hand, a study by Hsee et al. had subjects judge a person on the happy/sad dimension and found that words spoken with minimal variation in intonation had an impact about 4 times larger than face expressions seen in a film without sound.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Therefore, when considering certain non-verbal mannerisms such as facial expressions and physical cues, they can conflict in meaning when compared to spoken language and emotions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Different setups and scenarios would yield different responses and meanings when using both types of communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In other ways they can complement each other, provided they are used together wisely during a conversation.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This relationship between verbal and nonverbal cues has become prominent in digital learning environments.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] A study done by Schneider and Krieglstein (2022) concluded that the emphasis on facial expressions and gestures, and improved the student's quality of learning.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Participants who viewed lectures with a gesturing agent showed improved retention and transfer scores relative to those who did not.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The study found that students exposed to lectures incorporating gestures demonstrated higher comprehension and improved learning outcomes.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] These findings illustrate how nonverbal behaviors can influence the effectiveness of communication, which connects to broader strategies for improving nonverbal awareness.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Mindfulness is one technique that can help improve one's awareness of nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Those mindful and present to how their body moves can learn to better control their external nonverbal communication, which results in more effective communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] During communication, nonverbal messages can interact with verbal messages in six ways: repeating, conflicting, complementing, substituting, regulating and accenting/moderating.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Conflicting verbal and nonverbal messages within the same interaction can sometimes send opposing or conflicting messages.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] A person verbally expressing a statement of truth while simultaneously fidgeting or avoiding eye contact may convey a mixed message to the receiver in the interaction.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Conflicting messages may occur for a variety of reasons often stemming from feelings of uncertainty, ambivalence, or frustration.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] When mixed messages occur, nonverbal communication becomes the primary tool people use to attain additional information to clarify the situation; great attention is placed on bodily movements and positioning when people perceive mixed messages during interactions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Definitions of nonverbal communication creates a limited picture in our minds but there are ways to create a clearer one.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] There are different dimensions of verbal and nonverbal communication that have been discovered.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] They are (1) structure versus non-structure, (2) linguistic versus non-linguistic, (3) continuous versus discontinuous, (4) learned versus innate, and (5) left versus right hemispheric processing.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Accurate interpretation of messages is made easier when nonverbal and verbal communication complement each other.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal cues can be used to elaborate on verbal messages to reinforce the information sent when trying to achieve communicative goals; messages have been shown to be remembered better when nonverbal signals affirm the verbal exchange.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal behavior is sometimes used as the sole channel for communication of a message.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] People learn to identify facial expressions, body movements, and body positioning as corresponding with specific feelings and intentions.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal signals can be used without verbal communication to convey messages; when nonverbal behavior does not effectively communicate a message, verbal methods are used to enhance understanding.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Verbal communication is a highly structured form of communication with set rules of grammar.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The rules of verbal communication help to understand and make sense of what other people are saying.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For example, foreigners learning a new language can have a hard time making themselves understood.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] On the other hand, nonverbal communication has no formal structure when it comes to communicating.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal communication occurs without even thinking about it.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The same behavior can mean different things, such as crying of sadness or of joy.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Therefore, these cues need to be interpreted carefully to get their correct meaning.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] There are only a few assigned symbols in the system of nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nodding the head is one symbol that indicates agreement in some cultures, but in others, it means disagreement.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] On the other hand, verbal communication has a system of symbols that have specific meanings to them.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Verbal communication is based on discontinuous units whereas nonverbal communication is continuous.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Communicating nonverbally cannot be stopped unless one would leave the room, but even then, the intrapersonal processes still take place (individuals communicating with themselves).
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Without the presence of someone else, the body still manages to undergo nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For example, there are no other words being spoken after a heated debate, but there are still angry faces and cold stares being distributed.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This is an example of how nonverbal communication is continuous.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Learned non-verbal cues require a community or culture for their reinforcement.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For example, table manners are not innate capabilities upon birth.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Dress code is a non-verbal cue that must be established by society.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Hand symbols, whose interpretation can vary from culture to culture, are not innate nonverbal cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Learned cues must be gradually reinforced by admonition or positive feedback.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Innate non-verbal cues are "built-in" features of human behavior.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Generally, these innate cues are universally prevalent and regardless of culture.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For example, smiling, crying, and laughing do not require teaching.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Similarly, some body positions, such as the fetal position, are universally associated with weakness.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Due to their universality, the ability to comprehend these cues is not limited to individual cultures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This type of processing involves the neurophysiological approach to nonverbal communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] It explains that the right hemisphere processes nonverbal stimuli such as those involving spatial, pictorial, and gestalt tasks while the left hemisphere involves the verbal stimuli involving analytical and reasoning tasks.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] It is possible that individuals may not use the correct hemisphere at appropriate times when it comes to interpreting a message or meaning.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] From 1977 to 2004, the influence of disease and drugs on receptivity of nonverbal communication was studied by teams at three separate medical schools using a similar paradigm.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Researchers at the University of Pittsburgh, Yale University and Ohio State University had subjects observe gamblers at a slot machine awaiting payoffs.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The amount of this payoff was read by nonverbal transmission prior to reinforcement.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This technique was developed by and the studies directed by psychologist Robert E.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] These groups reported diminished receptive ability in heroin addicts and phencyclidine abusers, contrasted with increased receptivity in cocaine addicts.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Men with major depression manifested significantly decreased ability to read nonverbal cues when compared with euthymic men.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In some subjects tested for ability to read nonverbal cues, intuitive paradigms were apparently employed while in others a cause and effect approach was used.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Subjects in the former group answered quickly and before reinforcement occurred.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] They could not give a rationale for their particular responses.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Subjects in the latter category delayed their response and could offer reasons for their choice.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The level of accuracy between the two groups did not vary nor did handedness.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Obese women and women with premenstrual syndrome were found to also possess diminished abilities to read these cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In contradistinction, men with bipolar disorder possessed increased abilities.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] A woman with total paralysis of the nerves of facial expression was found unable to transmit or receive any nonverbal facial cues whatsoever.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Because of the changes in levels of accuracy on the levels of nonverbal receptivity, the members of the research team hypothesized a level of involvement of neurotransmitters when interpreting nonverbal cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Users of certain drugs had an enhanced ability while users of other drugs had a diminished ability.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Based on the available data, however, the primary cause and primary effect could not be sorted out on the basis of the paradigm employed.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The authors also hypothesised that it is possible that, for example, cocaine abusers do so because their pre-existing abilities helped them to conceal their drug abuse.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] An increased emphasis on gestures exists when intonations or facial expression are used.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] "Speakers often anticipate how recipients will interpret their utterances.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] If they wish some other, less obvious interpretation, they may "mark" their utterance (e.g. with special intonations or facial expressions)." This specific emphasis known as 'marking' can be spotted as a learned form of non-verbal communication in toddlers.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] A groundbreaking study from Carpenter et al. in the *Journal of Child Language* has concluded that the act of marking a gesture is recognized by three-year-olds but not by two-year-olds.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In the study, two and three-year-old toddlers were tested on their recognition of markedness within gestures.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The experiment was conducted in a room with an examiner and the test subjects, which for the first study were three-year-olds.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The examiner sat across from each child individually, and allowed them to play with various objects including a purse with a sponge in it and a box with a sponge in it.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] After allowing the child to play with the objects for three minutes, the examiner told the child it was time to clean up and motioned by pointing to the objects.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] They measured the responses of the children by first pointing and not marking the gesture, to see the child's reaction to the request and if they reached for the objects to clean them up.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] After observing the child's response, the examiner then asked and pointed again, marking the gesture with facial expression, as to lead the child to believe the objects were supposed to be cleaned up.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The results showed that three-year-old children were able to recognize the markedness, by responding to the gesture and cleaning the objects up as opposed to when the gesture was presented without being marked.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] In the second study in which the same experiment was performed on two-year-olds, the results were different.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] For the most part, the children did not recognize the difference between the marked and unmarked gesture by not responding more prevalently to the marked gesture, unlike the results of the three-year-olds.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Boone and Cunningham conducted a study to determine at which age children begin to recognize emotional meaning (happiness, sadness, anger and fear) in expressive body movements.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The study included 29 adults and 79 children divided into age groups of four-, five- and eight-year-olds.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The children were shown two clips simultaneously and were asked to point to the one that was expressing the target emotion.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The results of the study revealed that of the four emotions being tested the 4-year-olds were only able to correctly identify sadness at a rate that was better than chance.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The 5-year-olds performed better and were able to identify happiness, sadness and fear at better than chance levels.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The 8-year-olds and adults could correctly identify all four emotions and there was very little difference between the scores of the two groups.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Between the ages of 4 and 8, nonverbal communication and decoding skills improve dramatically.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] A study was conducted to determine how nonverbal communication and play amongst children, particularly autistic children, affects language development.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Mundy et. al. observed communication amongst groups of autistic children divided by diagnosed mental age from a sample of 16 children.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The study had observations of how the children played between each other using an assortment of items provided, such as a spoon, doll, toy car, toy telephone, sponge, and more.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The study concluded that there was little to no correlation between play and nonverbal communication, concluding in possible further psychological factors such as metacognitive awareness of pretending or delayed imitation within play being possible explanations for play development.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Little significance with the results of language acquisition was found, opening up discussion and further research due to outliers within the results.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Research indicates that emotional expressions differ across various positive, describing that emotions can be communicated vocally or expressively on someone's face.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] This suggests that nonverbal behaviors, such as facial expressions, may convey multiple meanings depending on context rather than a single, fixed emotion.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Regardless of whether emotions are expressed vocally or perceived nonverbally, they can appear in many different contexts, in which they are utilized to communicate more efficiently.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] 1For instance, in a healthcare setting, nurses rely on nonverbal behaviors in the case of hearing loss with a patient.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] A study conducted by Wanko Keutchafo concluded that effective nurse nonverbal communication with hospitalized older adults, is shaped by the nurse’s own intrinsic factors, including their attitudes and beliefs towards the patients.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The professional employs smiles and gentle eye contact to communicate safety and respect towards the older adults, as these patients rely more on visual cues.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Along with facial movement, they also use touch, such as gently placing a hand on a patients shoulder in attempt at reassurance.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Wanko Keutchafo EL, Kerr J, Baloyi OB, Duma SE.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] (2022) “Conditions Influencing Effective Nurse Nonverbal Communication With Hospitalized Older Adults in Cameroon”.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The use of space was also considered when dealing with slow approaches or sitting on a bed, in which some nurses refrained from this method due to a patient's cultural beliefs, which resulted in reduced communication.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] As for other interactions, such as students in a classroom setting, teachers may take advantage of indicating gestures, like pointing, to direct the children’s attention and highlight any mishaps.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] As introduced in the study “Nonverbal Communication in Classroom Interaction and Its Role in Italian Foreign Language Teaching and Learning” by Pierangela Diadori, these methods can be seen as pointing to one's feet, in representation of the meaning “today/now”.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Another is drawing a circle with their arms, to portray “working around an idea”.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Along with these behaviors, many instructors also use a fist pumping gesture to emphasize classroom energy or activity.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The study found that nonverbal behaviors play a central role in Italian foreign-language classrooms, functioning as a tool for both learning and teaching.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Nonverbal communication cues are integrated into the instructor’s practices to support comprehension and classroom management.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] A byproduct of the work of the Pittsburgh/Yale/Ohio State team was an investigation of the role of nonverbal facial cues in heterosexual nondate rape.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Males who were serial rapists of adult women were studied for nonverbal receptive abilities.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Their scores were the highest of any subgroup.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] It was reported that women who had been raped on at least two occasions by different perpetrators had a highly significant impairment in their abilities to read these cues in either male or female senders.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] These results were troubling, indicating a predator-prey model.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The authors did note that whatever the nature of these preliminary findings the responsibility of the rapist was in no manner or level diminished.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] The final target of study for this group was the medical students they taught.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Medical students at Ohio State University, Ohio University and Northeast Ohio Medical College were invited to serve as subjects.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Students indicating a preference for the specialties of family practice, psychiatry, pediatrics and obstetrics-gynecology achieved significantly higher levels of accuracy than those students who planned to train as surgeons, radiologists, or pathologists.
[src:nonverbal-communication/nonverbal-communication-p02] Internal medicine and plastic surgery candidates scored at levels near the mean.
